<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rain spread across the northern Plains and along the Rockies on  
Saturday, and showers from the edge of Hurricane Dennis hit parts 
of the Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and a few thunderstorms spread across large parts of  
Montana, with showers and some thundershowers stretching eastward 
through the Dakotas into Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms extended from South Dakota southward into  
Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	During the afternoon, isolated storms and showers also developed  
from Idaho and Wyoming across Utah and Colorado into Arizona, New 
Mexico and western Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Southeast, bands of showers on the far outskirts of  
Hurricane Dennis moved inland along the coasts of Florida, Georgia 
and the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	By late afternoon, the center of Dennis was about 180 miles east  
of Cape Canaveral, Fla., and moving toward the northwest. It was 
expected to turn more toward the north. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a few showers moved across Maine, the Ohio Valley and  
the Gulf Coast regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 43 at Elko, Nev., to a midday reading of 99 at 
Abilene, Texas. The lowest wind chill was 38 at Ely, Nev., and the 
highest heat index at midday was 110 at Beaufort, S.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
