<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane May Miss U.S. Coast  
</P>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- While a strengthened Hurricane Dennis  
struck the northern Bahamas today, there is hope among forecasters 
that the storm may veer away from the United States. The hurricane 
could make landfall around Tuesday, most likely somewhere in the 
Carolinas, forecasters said. But there's a ``glimmer of hope'' that 
this may not occur, said Jerry Jarrell, director of the National 
Hurricane Center in Miami. At 5 p.m. EDT today, Dennis was centered 
180 miles east of Florida's Cape Canaveral. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Alliance Presents Platform  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A powerful new Russian political alliance  
presented its centrist platform today for December parliamentary 
elections, saying the sweeping powers of the Russian presidency 
should be divided up. The Fatherland-All Russia alliance -- forged 
by Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, former Prime Minister Yevgeny 
Primakov and a group of regional governors -- proposed weakening the 
presidency in favor of giving more power to parliament and the 
prime minister. 

</P>
<P>
	Displaced Turks Need Solid Housing  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Days of heavy rains have added to the  
misery of Turkey's earthquake survivors camped out in muddy, 
rat-infested fields, and the task of replacing soggy, makeshift 
tents with solid housing has become more urgent. Some of Turkey's 
leading contractors, meeting with government officials in Ankara 
today, said they could build 60,000 prefabricated homes in three 
months, the Anatolia news agency reported. Damage from the Aug. 17 
quake has been estimated at $10 billion, and the government says as 
many as 600,000 have been left homeless. The death toll rose to 
13,893 today. 

</P>
<P>
	Union Recommends New Boeing Deal  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- After days of pessimistic talk that a strike was  
in the offing, the Machinists union today recommended that 44,000 
Boeing workers accept a new contract with the aerospace company. A 
proposal offered by the company early today is ``the best contract 
in the aerospace industry,'' said Bill Johnson, president of 
Machinists District Lodge 751. The workers will vote on the pact 
Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Burton Calls for Hearings on FBI  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prompted by the latest furor over federal law  
enforcement's conduct during the final, fateful hours in the 1993 
standoff with the Branch Davidians, Congress is scurrying to review 
years-old hearing records and organize a fresh round of inquiries. 
Congressional ire was raised with the FBI's admission Wednesday 
that incendiary tear gas grenades were lobbed near the Davidians' 
compound outside Waco, Texas. House Government Reform Committee 
Chairman Dan Burton pledged to convene hearings, calling them 
``absolutely essential.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs Don't Feel Safe in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	GNJILANE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- As Kosovo Serbs across the province  
complain that they do not feel safe -- and ethnic Albanians conced 
that protecting Serbs is a problem -- the idea of ethnic segregation 
is being openly discussed at the highest levels of the U.N. and 
NATO commands. Over the past week, local Serb leaders proposed 
creating separate areas where Serbs could live apart from ethnic 
Albanians, protected by international peacekeepers and governing 
themselves. The idea runs counter to the stated goal of the United 
Nations and NATO, and ethnic Albanian leaders oppose it. 

</P>
<P>
	Starr Joined by Justice Dept.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton Justice Department has joined  
Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr to appeal a judge's ruling on 
alleged grand jury leaks during the Monica Lewinsky investigation, 
legal sources say. At issue is whether the independent counsel 
improperly leaked secret grand jury information to the news media. 
The Justice Department may be worried that the court is setting an 
unreasonable precedent making it difficult for their own 
prosecutors to give reporters information. 

</P>
<P>
	Somalian Clans Intensify Fights  
</P>
<P>
	MOGADISHU, Somalia (AP) -- Embroiled in sporadic battles for the  
past four monts, rival clan-based factions intensified fighting 
over control of the key Somali port of Kismayo and other southern 
towns, reports from the region indicated today. The fighters 
backing Gen. Mohamed Saed Hirsi, better known as Morgan, forced the 
Somali National Front out of the Hosingo, retaking the town just 
months after they lost it, Gen. Abdurahman Khalif Dhi'is told 
reporters in Mogadishu by radio. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Wins Little League World Series  
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- Osaka, Japan, beat Phenix City, Ala.,  
5-0 in the championship game of the Little League World Series 
today. Kazuki Sumiyama struck out nine, including three of Phenix 
City's first four batters. Only Zach Martin and Cory Rasmus got 
hits, both singles, off Sumiyama, who throws a fastball and 
variations his teammates call the ``Kazuball'' and the 
``Thunderball.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
