<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sosa, McGwire Chase 70 HRs Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Home run history might be repeating itself.  
</P>
<P>
	As their teams stagger to the finish of disappointing seasons,  
Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire are staging an encore to the race that 
revived the game last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Homer No. 70, as distant as a faraway star not too long ago,  
suddenly seems possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Can they reach that unfathomable number as McGwire did last  
season, when he edged out Sosa by four? Can they top the drama? Who 
knows? It's still the best show around. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa headed into the weekend with 53 home runs, leading McGwire  
by two, with five weeks and more than 30 games left. Sosa was ahead 
of last year's pace, while McGwire was right on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those guys are trying to feed off each other,'' said Cubs  
hitting coach Jeff Pentland, who helped Sosa reduce his wild swings 
outside of the strike zone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really believe that is a part of it. I think that is an  
incentive for both guys. When you get players to elevate their 
games emotionally, I think you see special things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So, here they go again.  
</P>
<P>
	The watered-down expansion pitching might be part of the reason.  
So might be the tightly wound baseballs that pop out of parks or 
the homer-friendly stadiums of a new generation. Mostly, it's two 
powerful hitters doing what no one has done before. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire and Sosa will tell you they're not watching each other,  
that they're team players upset by the dismal seasons. That's one 
major difference from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, McGwire and the Cardinals were playing out the schedule  
while Sosa and the Cubs were making the playoffs. Now both teams 
are going home when the season ends. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like last year, because we were in the middle of a  
race and Mark and I were chasing a record that had stood for 37 
years,'' Sosa said, referring to Roger Maris' 61 homers in 1961. 
``The team is not playing the way it did last year. But because the 
direction the team goes is not good it doesn't mean I have to go 
there, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year McGwire and Sosa homered 21 times on the same day.  
Through Aug. 14 this year when they traded three-run shots in St. 
Louis, Big Mac and Slammin' Sammy have homered on the same day 16 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take care of myself. He takes care of himself,'' McGwire  
said of Sosa, who has become a friend. ``I have no control over 
anybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire and Sosa will go head-to-head six more times, first at  
Wrigley Sept. 20-22 and then to end the season Oct. 1-3 in St. 
Louis. They both should be swinging for the fences. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe me, they want to hit homers,'' Colorado's Dante  
Bichette said. ``You don't become that good at hitting home runs by 
flaring balls to right field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the Cubs and Cards met last September at Busch Stadium,  
McGwire tied Maris, then passed him with the historic No. 62 the 
next night off Chicago's Steve Trachsel. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa ran in from right field to congratulate his rival, and they  
exchanged their familiar greetings -- McGwire's fake punch to the 
stomach, Sosa's two-finger salute to the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa took the lead briefly on Sept. 25 with his 66th, but  
McGwire answered with his 66th the same night, then hit four more 
to reach the new magic number. 
</P>
<P>
	That's how they pushed one another, making what they  
accomplished seem more human, appealing even to people who didn't 
count themselves as baseball fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa had a 51-48 lead earlier this month before McGwire caught  
up. Sosa then broke the tie with his 52nd and at one point was 
eight games ahead of his pace from last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not on my mind right now. I'm trying to survive,'' Sosa  
said after the Cubs had lost 50 out of 70 games. ``Pretty much I'm 
not thinking about the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa's feel-good approach to the hype last season seemed to ease  
the pressure on both of the sluggers. Now the attention that 
enveloped them in 1998 will only increase again in the season's 
final weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``People say to me every day, `Are you going top hit a home run  
today?''' McGwire said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like they're asking will I walk down the street today. I  
wish it was easy but it's not. Not many players hit 40-50 a year. 
People talk about how there are so many home runs hit this year. So 
what? The game has changed. The players are really, really good. 
But if you look at the end product on Oct. 3, you'll see the same 
names you've seen the last couple of years leading in home runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire doubted No. 70 would be reached this season.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think 60 will be gotten again. Seventy is just an extra  
10,'' he said. ``It is unfathomable when you think I hit five the 
last three days'' of last season. 
</P>
<P>
	But it could happen, especially with McGwire and Sosa. Pentland  
said the advent of videotape is one thing that has helped hitters 
everywhere, allowing them to make adjustments from at-bat to at-bat 
and avoid too many slumps. 
</P>
<P>
	But mainly it comes down to sheer power for McGwire, a man many  
think can challenge Hank Aaron's all-time record of 755, and for 
Sosa, whose muscular body and rip-the-shirt-off-his-back swing has 
made him a worthy adversary. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big thing I've always told Sammy and the same is true with  
Mark is that he has a special gift,'' Pentland said. '' He is able 
to swing and hit the ball a long way and there is no reason to try 
and hit it 900 feet. It's built into their bodies when they have 
that kind of physical talent.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
