<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Aug. 28, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	East Coast Beachgoers on Watch  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- East Coast beachgoers and coastal  
residents kept a watch on changing weather forecasts Saturday as 
Hurricane Dennis added muscle while moving slowly through the 
Bahamas. At 11 p.m. EDT, Dennis had strengthened, with its 
sustained wind accelerating to 105 mph, and was centered about 325 
miles southeast of Charleston, S.C., the hurricane center said. A 
hurricane watch was issued from north of Savannah, Ga. to Surf 
City, N.C. Various computer models suggested it could affect the 
coast of the Carolinas late Monday or Tuesday, or veer away from 
land, forecasters said. 

</P>
<P>
	China To Raise Unemployment Funds  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China will raise stipends to unemployed workers  
by 30 percent as part of a series of measures intended to arrest 
the economic slide and brighten public sentiment ahead of the 
country's 50th anniversary of communist rule. Unemployment has 
soared as once centrally planned industries trim bloated payrolls 
to cope with free-market reforms. With millions of Chinese trying 
to survive on meager stipends, the communist leadership has worried 
about the potential for unrest. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs Wary of Peacekeepers Abilities  
</P>
<P>
	GNJILANE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Complaints from Kosovo Serbs who say  
they do not feel safe and can't rely on peacekeepers to protect 
them are raising questions over whether NATO and the United Nations 
can establish a multiethnic Kosovo. Even ethnic Albanians concede 
that adequately protecting Serbs is a problem. As a result, the 
idea of ethnic segregation -- once a taboo subject -- is being openly 
discussed at the highest levels of the U.N. and NATO commands. 

</P>
<P>
	Firefighters Make Progress in West  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With more than 200,000 acres burned by wildfire,  
firefighters in the Western states were making progress Saturday on 
the blazes, though hot weather and frequent lightning strikes 
continued to pose a threat. Nineteen large fires were burning in 
California, Nevada, Oregon and Texas, though nine were expected to 
be contained tomorrow. More than half of the fires were in Northern 
California, drawing more than 7,000 firefighters. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Endorses Charter Schools  
</P>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton Saturday used his  
weekly radio address to denounce the Republicans' $792 billion 
tax-cut package as unacceptably risky and announce $95 million in 
aid for charter schools. After leaving Martha's Vineyard, the 
Clinton family then left the island for a house-hunting trip to 
Westchester County, N.Y., near New York City, and a weekend of 
fund-raising parties in the wealthy seashore suburbs of Long 
Island. 

</P>
<P>
	Mideast Talks Linger on Prisoners Issue  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators trying to  
iron out differences in order to clear the way for Israel's 
withdrawal from 11 percent of the West Bank are stuck on one 
significant issue: the release of Palestinian prisoners. 
Negotiators tried Saturday to resolve the final barriers ahead of a 
visit to the region by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. 
Albright is expected to participate Thursday in a signing ceremony 
in Alexandria, Egypt, if the agreement is worked out in time. The 
peace deal would be the first to be signed under the rule of 
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. 

</P>
<P>
	Rabid Bear a Concern in Iowa  
</P>
<P>
	CLERMONT, Iowa (AP) -- As many as 100 people may have been  
exposed to a bear cub that died of rabies at a rural northeastern 
Iowa petting zoo. State health official said visitors who had come 
in contact with the bear in the past month should see a doctor 
immediately. The 5-month-old black bear, which was on display at 
the Wild Midwest Petting Zoo in Clermont, died Friday afternoon. 

</P>
<P>
	Penn State Trounces Arizona 41-7  
</P>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Kevin Thompson threw for two  
touchdowns, Chafie Fields ran 70 yards for a score and caught a 
37-yard pass for another Saturday and the third-ranked Nittany 
Lions overwhelmed No. 4 Arizona 41-7 in the Pigskin Classic. Penn 
State's highly touted defense exceeded even its own expectations by 
shutting down Arizona's high-powered offense on the way to a 31-0 
halftime lead. 

</P>
<P>
	Venus Williams Wins Pilot Pen  
</P>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Venus Williams, the 19-year-old with the  
best serve in women's tennis, beat Lindsay Davenport 6-2, 7-5 to 
win the Pilot Pen championship. Williams' No. 3 world ranking is 
the highest in her five-year career. Williams and Davenport battled 
from the baseline for most of the one hour, 24 minute match as 
their hard-hitting styles kept them well off the net. Williams had 
the speed to track down Davenport's rifle returns and the 
athleticism to turn them into points. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
