<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Union Deadline Passes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Contract talks between Boeing Co. and its largest  
union continued early Saturday as both sides let slide an informal 
Friday midnight deadline for the aerospace company to present its 
final offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Company chairman Phil Condit said earlier Friday the company  
faced ``reasonably good'' odds of avoiding a strike by its 
machinists, despite pessimism expressed by union officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides had said the company's final contract proposal was  
expected to be delivered by midnight Friday to the International 
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers union, which 
represents 44,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're continuing to work and talk and exchange information,''  
Boeing spokesman Larry McCracken said early Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still a ways apart,'' said union spokesman Tim Flynn,  
who agreed the two sides were still talking. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is seeking to preserve jobs, improve medical benefits  
and increase pensions. The company wants to cut costs through 
subcontracting, paying less for health benefits and adopting a 
flexible work week. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks come as Boeing is undertaking a massive job cut  
program. From a high of 238,000 in June 1998, Boeing plans to 
reduce its work force to between 185,000 and 195,000 by the end of 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The average machinist at Boeing earns $40,000 a year, not  
counting benefits or overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The current 44-month contract covers 31,000 workers in  
Washington state, 1,400 in Portland, Ore., and 11,600 in Wichita, 
Kan. Boeing employs about 210,000 worldwide. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
