<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Show Ban Shot Down in St. Paul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL (AP) -- An effort to ban gun shows on city property has  
been shot down by the city attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	In a memo sent Friday to City Council members, Assistant City  
Attorney Philip Byrne wrote that the resolution ``does not have the 
force and effect of law'' and cannot be used to ``breach existing 
contracts or obligations that the city might have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne said the council could still ban gun shows but would have  
to pass an administrative ordinance, a process more complicated 
than adopting a resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban passed 4-3 on Wednesday, less than a week after four  
people were injured when a gun discharged during a RiverCentre 
weapons show last Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Terrance Stafford, 49, was charged Thursday with reckless  
discharge of a firearm for taking a .22-caliber pistol off a 
display table, loading a round and firing at the floor during the 
Weapons Collectors Association show. 
</P>
<P>
	Councilman Jerry Blakey, the council's most outspoken voice on  
gun control, said he would meet with gun association and 
RiverCentre representatives as well as with Police Chief William 
Finney next week to talk about ways to make gun shows safer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
