<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spain's Anton Wins Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Spain's Abel Anton delighted a home crowd  
at Olympic Stadium Saturday, using his finishing kick over the last 
12 minutes to win his second straight World Championships marathon 
and Spain's second gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Anton, 36, finished in 2 hours, 13 minutes, 36 seconds, with  
Italy's Vincenzo Modica (2:14:03) finishing second and Nobuyuki 
Sato of Japan (2:14:07) earning the bronze medal. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Spain's third straight gold in the World Championships  
marathon, with Martin Fiz winning in 1995 and taking second to 
Anton in '97. 
</P>
<P>
	At the start of the race, the temperature was 97 degrees,  
creating some of the toughest conditions ever for a major marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	At the finish, as Anton entered the stadium greeted by thousands  
of fluttering yellow and red Spanish flags, the temperature had 
dropped to 86 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	Anton caught Sato with about 12 minutes left, paced him for  
about 90 seconds, and then pulled away relentlessly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
