<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Fires Back at Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FALCON HEIGHTS, Minn. (AP) -- Pro-wrestler-turned-Gov. Jesse  
Ventura is flexing his vocal chords in a beef with a Minnesota 
newspaper that criticized him for returning to the ring as a 
referee, claiming he was setting a bad example for kids by 
promoting sex and violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura said the Saint Paul Pioneer Press' criticism of pro  
wrestling's staged mayhem and scantily clad women was hypocritical 
because the paper runs advertisements for X-rated movies and strip 
clubs in its sports section, which children read. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknaming the paper the ``Saint Paul Pioneer Porn,'' Ventura  
said he was canceling his subscription and would deny any future 
interview requests from its reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Saint Paul Pioneer Press is triple-X,'' Ventura said  
Friday on his weekly radio show. ``They are lining their pockets 
with pornography. They are working together with the X-rated 
industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue here really is that the governor doesn't like to be  
criticized,'' editor Walker Lundy said, adding that the paper can't 
legally deny advertising space to sexually-oriented businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura retired from wrestling in 1986  
because of an injury. He took part in a recent pay-per-view 
wrestling event as a referee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
