<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemon Drop Kid Wins $1M Travers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Lemon Drop Kid proved to be the  
Big Horse in a big race for the second time in three months when he 
won Saturday's $1 million Travers at Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belmont Stakes winner won by three-quarters of a length over  
Vision and Verse. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1 1/2-mile Belmont on June 5, Lemon Drop Kid beat Vision and  
Verse by a head. 
</P>
<P>
	Third in the Travers on a sunny Saturday was 8-5 favorite  
Menifee, who was 1 3/4 lengths behind Vision and Verse and 1 3/4 in front 
of stablemate Ecton Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was a step toward a possible 3-year-old championship  
for Lemon Drop Kid. His trainer, Scotty Schulhofer, had said before 
the race that his colt would need to win a couple races to take the 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	The division leader continues to be Charismatic, the Kentucky  
Derby and Preakness winner who was retired after breaking an ankle 
while finishing third in the Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid, ridden by Jose Santos, carried level weight of  
126 pounds over 1 1/4 miles on a fast track in 2:02. He paid $9.30, 
$5.80 and $3.20 for his third victory in seven starts this year and 
earned $600,000 to boost his career earnings to $1,541,470. 
</P>
<P>
	Vision and Verse, ridden by Shane Sellers, paid $11.80 and $4.90  
and Menifee, ridden by Pat Day, was $2.50 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid, owned by Jeanne Vance, was fourth entering the  
backstretch and had moved to third behind Cat Thief and Vision and 
Verse with a half-mile to go. 
</P>
<P>
	Vision and Verse had taken the lead with Lemon Drop Kid second  
at the quarter pole. Those two then battled through the stretch 
before Lemon Drop Kid took the lead just inside the sixteenth pole 
and held on to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee was blocked on the inside on the run down the  
backstretch but the Haskell Invitational winner made a late but 
futile run in the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Completing the order of finish were Best of Luck, Badger Gold,  
Cat Thief and Unbridled Jet. 
</P>
<P>
	In another stakes for 3-year-olds, Forestry ($5.50) won the  
$200,000 King's Bishop by 1 1/2 lengths over Five Star Day in 1:21 for 
seven furlongs, just 2-5 of a second off the track record. It was 
the sixth victory in the last seven races for Forestry, ridden by 
Chris Antley and trained by Bob Baffert. 
</P>
<P>
	In the $150,000 Fourstardave Handicap, Comic Strip ($14), ridden  
by Day, beat Divide and Conquer by 2 1/2 lengths in 1:41 3-5 for 1 
1-16 miles on a soft turf course. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
