<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Show a Target of L.A. Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Emboldened by a shooting rampage in its own  
backyard, Los Angeles County is trying to shut down weapons sales 
at the nation's largest gun show, igniting a volatile battle 
between California firearms sellers and anti-gun forces. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote last week by the small but politically powerful Board  
of Supervisors to ban gun sales on county property is part of a 
groundswell in California, where Gov. Gray Davis signed three 
weapons-related laws on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the right thing to do,'' said Supervisor Zev  
Yaroslavsky, whose ordinance won initial approval on a 3-2 vote and 
is headed to a second vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Real people, the people in supermarkets and in the corridors  
of the county buildings, are stunned that the county is profiting 
from guns,'' he said in an interview. ``Why are we facilitating the 
sale and distribution of weapons?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ordinance would hit hard at the Great Western Gun Show,  
which boasts as many as 5,300 vendor tables and draws up to 35,000 
people to each of its four annual events at the Los Angeles County 
fairgrounds in Pomona. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote came just two weeks after a gunman shot up a Jewish  
community center in the San Fernando Valley, wounding three little 
boys, a teen-age girl and a woman, and then gunned down a postal 
worker delivering mail nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	The assault also revived memories of the notorious 1997 North  
Hollywood bank robbery shootout between police and two gunmen in 
body armor firing automatic rifles. More than a dozen people were 
wounded before the robbers went down. 
</P>
<P>
	But those who defend the right to gun ownership remain adamant  
in their views. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Los Angeles Board of Supervisors has behaved immorally,''  
raged Wallace Beinfeld, head of the National Association of Arms 
Shows. 
</P>
<P>
	In spite of recent revelations that some guns possessed by the  
North Hollywood gunmen came from the Great Western Gun Show, 
Beinfeld insisted, ``Bad guys stay away from gun shows. They're 
better off buying guns at kitchen tables.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The show has had only four arrests in 20 years, he claimed,  
adding, ``That's safer than Disneyland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beinfeld downplayed a recent sting operation by California  
Attorney General Bill Lockyer's undercover agents that found 
illegal weapons so readily available at the Great Western Gun Show 
that agents ran out money. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockyer said his agents were able to buy modified assault  
weapons, flame thrower kits, a rocket launcher and kits to convert 
guns into illegal automatic weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents also said they witnessed the selling of handguns to  
people who were not asked to wait 10 days for a background check, 
as required by law. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one asked for any background checks, waiting periods, no  
paperwork,'' Lockyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	County Supervisor Mike Antonovich voted against the gun show ban  
and denounced it as political grandstanding that penalizes the 
law-abiding. 
</P>
<P>
	``The solution to gun violence is a zero-tolerance policy  
against criminals who use guns, and enforcing the law to confiscate 
guns from convicted felons,'' Antonovich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Antonovich also predicted the ordinance would lead to costly  
litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, lawsuits are being threatened, and worse. Yaroslavsky is  
being inundated with anti-Semitic e-mail and hate letters. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the most intense set of anti-Semitic letters I've ever  
received,'' he said. ``I've received hate mail for years but none 
of it could add up to what I've gotten in the last week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The intensity may lie in numbers that make the vote more  
significant than the usual local government action. With 9.8 
million in Los Angeles County, each board member has a constituency 
of nearly 2 million people, making the supervisors some of the most 
powerful elected officials in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The action is part of a gun-control groundswell.  
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles County Sheriff Lee Baca and Los Angeles Police Chief  
Bernard Parks have taken strong positions for gun control since the 
Jewish center shooting. The three weapons-related laws signed by 
Gov. Davis on Friday impose tougher manufacturing standards on 
handguns, require the sale of trigger locks with guns, and increase 
regulations at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Seger, manager of the Great Western show, fired off a news  
release accusing Yaroslavsky of ``attempting to destroy the 
livelihood of not only the Great Western Show but of 2,000 
exhibitors from all over the world to buy sell and trade all types 
of items.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He maintained that only 10 percent of tables at the exhibition  
contain modern firearms and the rest sell such things as military 
memorabilia, fishing gear, clothing for outdoorsmen, jewelry and 
Indian artifacts. 
</P>
<P>
	Yaroslavsky said all those items could be sold under the new  
ordinance, but on-site sales of firearms and ammunition would be 
banned. Weapons may be displayed but a buyer would have to go to a 
seller's place of business to make the purchase. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
