<HEADLINE>  Hurricane Threatens Bahamas, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Whipping up gale-force winds that doubled  
over coconut palms and storm surges that crashed onto roadways, 
Hurricane Dennis closed in on the northern Bahamas today and 
threatened to strike near Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters said Dennis could strengthen and hit the United  
States as a major storm today, clawing up the Florida coast and 
heading into North Carolina by Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	From hundreds of miles away, Dennis kicked up 8-foot-high waves  
off Florida and North Carolina, delighting surfers but prompting 
officials to put state troopers and the National Guard on alert. 
Hurricane watches and tropical storm warnings were issued along 
hundreds of miles of the eastern seaboard. 
</P>
<P>
	At 8 a.m. EDT, the 90-mph hurricane was 25 miles northeast of  
Abaco -- a sliver of an island no more than 10 miles wide with a 
population of several thousand -- and some 240 miles southeast of 
Cape Canaveral in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's dangerous because some of the homes in Abaco are not well  
structured, and the hurricane is mighty close,'' said Jeffrey 
Simmons, a forecaster at the Bahamas Meteorological Office. 
``They're getting the worst of it at this time, but we won't have 
an assessment of any damage until later in the day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the island of Grand Bahama further west ``was also  
getting gusts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis' hurricane force winds broadened overnight to 40 miles  
from its center. Basil Dean, acting chief of meteorological 
services in the Bahamas, said the hurricane, which was in a 
near-stall Friday night, had resumed a slow west-northwest track 
near 6 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. National Weather Service reported that Dennis formed a  
fully formed eye Friday night, indicating it was getting stronger, 
and projected it would become a Category 3 hurricane packing winds 
of at least 111 mph within 48 hours. After that, it said, ``things 
become a bit more uncertain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A hurricane watch remained effect for the east coast of Florida  
from Sebastian Inlet northward to Fernandina Beach, 
</P>
<P>
	At the U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami, director Jerry  
Jarrell said Dennis could hit the United States as a major storm, 
around South Carolina. The center warned Bahamian islands in its 
path could suffer ``large and dangerous battering waves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're afraid might happen is that it'll just go a little  
bit inland and then go up the coast and that would really be a bad 
situation,'' Jarrell said. ``That would give you probably the 
maximum storm surge, the maximum heavy rain and probably the most 
damage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Abaco, hotel owner Rudy Malone boarded up in his house Friday  
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's here! It's here right now!'' he said. The howling wind  
``is very strong, it sounds like a train ... I can hear branches 
breaking off trees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People began preparing for the storm, banging wood over windows,  
battening down roofs and stocking up on supplies from the Bahamas 
to the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Carolina, Gov. Jim Hodges ordered 1,000 National Guard  
troops and 500 state troopers to prepare for duty, but no decision 
has been made on whether to evacuate people from the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	In North Carolina, 150,000 coastal residents were put on alert,  
as were state troopers and emergency management personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Shrimp boats returned early to Port Canaveral, and the South  
Florida Water Management District lowered water levels in canals to 
lessen the risk of flooding in heavy rains. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis was expected to strengthen over the next 24 hours and  
bring up to 10 inches of rain and tides up to 8 feet above normal. 
</P>
<P>
	On Abaco, as clouds blackened by sheets of rain gathered and  
wind gusts reached 55 mph, islanders huddled behind battened down 
windows or rushed to shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	Leeland Russell, assistant superintendent of police at Marsh  
Harbour on Abaco, said the storm was expected to pass over or near 
Crossing Rock, a settlement of mainly elderly people, who were in 
shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	Bahamasair, the national airline, canceled service to the Abaco  
islands and most of Eleuthera and telephone operators said some 
lines were down and other circuits overloaded by traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	On Eleuthera island, ``the winds have been fierce ... the oceans  
have been very raging,'' said hotel owner Sharon Rolle. ``It's 
difficult for cars to pass by because there are waves coming over -- 
straight over -- the main road so it would cover your cars.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
