<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Facts About Top Seeds at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A quick look at the seeded players in the U.S.  
Open tennis championships being played Aug. 30-Sept. 12 at the USTA 
National Tennis Center in Flushing Meadows: 
</P>
<P>
                              *Women    	
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 1 Martina Hingis    	
</P>
<P>
	Although she won the Australian Open in January and has regained  
the No. 1 ranking, Martina Hingis is trying to put her winning game 
back together after losing the French Open final to Steffi Graf, 
then being shocked by Jelena Dokic in the first round at Wimbledon. 
While she is still a marvelous all-court player with great 
anticipation and every shot in the book, other players are finding 
ways to beat Hingis. 
</P>
<P>
                       *No. 2 Lindsay Davenport    	
</P>
<P>
	The defending U.S. Open champion, the 6-foot-2, 175-pound  
right-hander won her second Grand Slam tournament title in 
impressive fashion, beating Steffi Graf in the Wimbledon final. 
While she hasn't dominated the hard court circuit this year, 
Davenport comes into the U.S. Open full of confidence. 
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 3 Venus Williams    	
</P>
<P>
	Venus has the game to win it all: huge serve, big forehand,  
penetrating backhand, quick feet, great range. And neither Venus 
nor her sister, seventh-seeded Serena, lack confidence. She has 
wins over all the top players, but not in the biggest tournaments 
of all, the majors. Perhaps this is the year. 
</P>
<P>
                         *No. 4. Monica Seles    	
</P>
<P>
	Once the dominating force in women's tennis, Seles has shown  
that she can again be a factor in the big tournaments. But she now 
stands on or behind the baseline instead of inside, her angles 
aren't quite as sharp, nor does she seem to hit the ball as hard. 
That, however, could be because everyone else is hitting the ball 
harder. 
</P>
<P>
                         *No. 5. Mary Pierce    	
</P>
<P>
	One of the hardest hitters in women's tennis, Pierce has always  
been hampered by her lack of mobility. The French woman, who has 
had a series of nagging injuries, has yet to win a title in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 6 Amanda Coetzer    	
</P>
<P>
	It's sometimes hard to figure out how this little South African  
-- she stands only 5-foot-2 -- can be ranked so high. And while she 
has yet to win a Grand Slam tournament, Coetzer's consistency, hard 
work and doggedness means she always around when the quarterfinals 
are played. 
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 7 Serena Williams    	
</P>
<P>
	Father Richard Williams said Serena will eventually be the  
better of the two Williams sisters. She has won three tournaments 
this year, posting victories over the top players. It's lack of 
experience that could keep her out of the winner's circle at 
Flushing Meadow until the next century. 
</P>
<P>
                         *No. 8 Jana Novotna    	
</P>
<P>
	Winning Wimbledon in 1998 was the apex of her career, and she  
has since played that way. One of the few serve-and-volleyers in 
the women's game, at age 30 Novotna is a half-step slower and more 
error-prone with her forehand. 
</P>
<P>
                     *No. 9 Julie Halard-Decugis    	
</P>
<P>
	Has been consistent this year. And her experience gives her an  
edge over players with more weapons. 
</P>
<P>
                   *No. 10 Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario    	
</P>
<P>
	Like Coetzer, the 5-6 1/2 Sanchez-Vicario's forte has been her  
running down every shot and making her opponent hit yet another. 
But she seems to have lost a half-step and doesn't have a weapon to 
really hurt her opponent. 
</P>
<P>
                       *No. 11 Nathalie Tauziat    	
</P>
<P>
	Late in her career -- she's 31 -- the French woman has found  
success. But her game won't stand up to the power or the craftiness 
of the top teen-agers in the field. 
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 12 Barbara Schett    	
</P>
<P>
	An Austrian right-hander, Schett is capable of upsetting some of  
the top players, but not enough of them to win the U.S. 0pen. 
</P>
<P>
                      *No. 13 Dominique Van Roost    	
</P>
<P>
	Van Roost last year became the first Belgian to be ranked in the  
world's Top 10. This year the right-hander reached the 
quarterfinals at the Australian Open and the fourth round at 
Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
                       *No. 14 Sandrine Testud    	
</P>
<P>
	While dangerous, this French woman is not considered a contender  
in the year's final major. 
</P>
<P>
                       *No. 15 Amelie Mauresmo    	
</P>
<P>
	A French left-hander with heavy ground strokes, Mauresmo was a  
surprising finalist at the Australian Open in January. She won't 
get that far at Flushing Meadow. 
</P>
<P>
                      *No. 16 Conchita Martinez    	
</P>
<P>
	This Spaniard's big topspin shots took her to the Wimbledon  
title five years ago, and she has twice reached the semifinals of 
the U.S. Open. Her chances of doing it again, however, are growing 
slim. 
</P>
<P>
                               *Men    	
</P>
<P>
                         *No. 1 Pete Sampras    	
</P>
<P>
	Pete Sampras is going after history. He tied Roy Emerson by  
winning his 12th Grand Slam tournament men's singles title when he 
captured Wimbledon for the sixth time in July. Sampras has the 
game, the temperament and the confidence to win his fifth U.S. Open 
crown, although he is coming into the tournament after suffering a 
strained hip flexor. 
</P>
<P>
                         *No. 2 Andre Agassi    	
</P>
<P>
	When he won the French Open in June, Agassi became only the  
fifth man to win all four Grand Slam tournaments in a career, and 
the first American since Don Budge won all four in 1938. Agassi 
then reached the final at Wimbledon before falling to Sampras, yet 
took over the No. 1 ranking for three weeks, the first time Agassi 
had led the rankings since 1996. His return of serve makes him a 
strong candidate to win his second U.S. Open. His serve, however, 
is a liability. 
</P>
<P>
                      *No. 3 Yevgeny Kafelnikov    	
</P>
<P>
	He could cap an up-and-down year with his first U.S. Open crown.  
The Russian right-hander began the year by winning the Australian 
Open. Then, after suffering six straight opening-round defeats, 
Kafelnikov took over the No. 1 ranking before promptly losing 
again. If he is confident, Kafelnikov could be a factor. If he's 
not, he might not get through the first round. 
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 4 Patrick Rafter    	
</P>
<P>
	Rafter's serve-and-volley game fits perfectly on the hard courts  
of Arthur Ashe Stadium, where he has won the last two U.S. Opens. 
He seemed ready to do it again before he had to pull out of his 
last two tournaments with tendinitis in his right shoulder. The key 
is whether the shoulder will hold up through the entire two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 5 Gustavo Kuerten    	
</P>
<P>
	The Brazilian right-hander has become much more consistent since  
he was a surprising winner at the French Open in 1997. He has a 
powerful baseline game, yet is not afraid to come to the net when 
he gets a short ball. 
</P>
<P>
                          *No. 6 Tim Henman    	
</P>
<P>
	It's been a long time since a British player has been one of the  
favorites to win a Grand Slam men's singles title, but Tim Henman 
fits that bill with a strong serve and crisp net play. 
</P>
<P>
                          *No. 7 Todd Martin    	
</P>
<P>
	Missed most of 1997 with injuries, but has come back strongly  
behind his big serve. The right-hander's biggest problem has been 
his court coverage. 
</P>
<P>
                          *No. 8 Carlos Moya    	
</P>
<P>
	One of the best clay court players in the game, Moya last year  
showed that he could play on hard court, reaching the semifinals at 
the National Tennis Center. 
</P>
<P>
                         *No. 9 Greg Rusedski    	
</P>
<P>
	A British Davis Cup teammate of Tim Henman, Rusedski has a big  
left-handed serve that took him to the U.S. Open final in 1997. He 
is coming off his latest injury and has not played much this 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
                         *No. 10 Marcelo Rios    	
</P>
<P>
	American Davis Cup captain Tom Gullikson said of Rios: ``Always  
talented, always dangerous, always moody.'' Enough said of the 
talented left-hander. 
</P>
<P>
                      *No. 11 Mark Philippoussis    	
</P>
<P>
	Was a U.S. Open finalist last year, but has missed his last two  
tournaments with tendinitis in his right shoulder, an injury that 
also sidelined him earlier in the year. 
</P>
<P>
                       *No. 12 Richard Krajicek    	
</P>
<P>
	Another big server, this Dutchman won Wimbledon in 1996. He has  
reached the fourth round at Flushing Meadow, but not since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 13 Alex Corretja    	
</P>
<P>
	A baseliner, the Spanish right-hander has shown he can win on  
most surfaces, capturing the year-ending ATP Tour World 
Championship on carpet last year after reaching the fourth round at 
the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
                          *No. 14 Tommy Haas    	
</P>
<P>
	Haas and Kiefer have carried German hopes into the top 20 in the  
world. The 21-year-old right-hander has victories over Agassi, 
Kafelnikov and Henman. 
</P>
<P>
                        *No. 15 Nicolas Kiefer    	
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer, a right-hander, has a perfect record against Rafter,  
beating the Australian three times. He also has victories over 
Kafelnikov, Kuerten and Henman. 
</P>
<P>
                       *No. 16 Nicolas Lapentti    	
</P>
<P>
	Lapentti has zoomed up the rankings, becoming No. 16 when he won  
the Indianapolis tournament a week ago, his first title in almost 
four years. He's reached the quarterfinals or better in five of his 
last six tournaments. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
