<DOCNO> APW19990828.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 00:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smith's Sprinters Steal World Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Maybe they should create a new entry on  
the medals table at the World Championships: HSI. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the name of the team of runners who train in Los Angeles  
under the tutelage of sprint guru John Smith and manager Emmanuel 
Hudson. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, HSI (which stands both for Hudson Smith International  
and Handling Speed Intelligently) sprinters have won three gold 
medals and one silver at the championships, with the chance for 
more in the relays this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	HSI won two more gold medals Friday night, with Maurice Greene  
and Inger Miller streaking to victories in the 200-meter dashes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning is contagious among the club,'' Smith said.  
</P>
<P>
	Miller went first, winning her race in a sparkling 21.77  
seconds, her best time ever and fastest in the world this year. It 
was her first major championship victory, topping the silver medal 
she won in the 100 last Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene dominated a modest field for his first major 200 title in  
19.90 seconds, his fastest time of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, who won the 100 title in 9.80 seconds, became the first  
man to complete the double at a major global meet since Carl Lewis 
swept both short sprints at the 1984 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``After I saw Inger win, I knew I had to go out there and do it  
for the team,'' Greene said. 
</P>
<P>
	The celebrations that followed resembled a family reunion, with  
Greene, Smith, Hudson and Miller sharing hugs all around. 
</P>
<P>
	The most emotional moment came when Greene and Miller broke into  
tears as they held each other in a long, tight embrace. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inger and me got very close this week,'' Greene said. ``We  
came here to do a job. She stood by me when I won the 100. We 
achieved what we came here to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene also shed tears on the medal stand, just as he did in  
1997 when he won his first world 100 title in Athens, Greece. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is what I've worked all year for,'' said Greene, who can  
win a third gold in the 400-meter relay this weekend. ``Those were 
tears of joy. I'm still crying inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene said he was just as happy for Miller, who joined the  
Smith camp last year after being coached her entire career by her 
father, Lennox, the 1968 Olympic silver medalist and 1972 bronze 
medalist in the 100. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a little more proud for Inger than for myself,'' Greene  
said. ``I've seen what she's been through and all the changes she's 
had to make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's group also includes Trinidad's Ato Boldon, the 1997  
world 200 champion who missed the championships with an injury, and 
U.S. sprinter Jon Drummond. 
</P>
<P>
	``The union of Maurice and Inger helped both of them,'' Hudson  
said. ``The difference between this year and last year for Inger is 
that she has training partners. Maurice is like her coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old Miller lauded the camaraderie of the HSI camp,  
where the sprinters train, eat and go out together, and tease and 
playfully trash-talk each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``To run as part of John Smith's group is like having an  
extended family,'' Miller said. ``We are all brothers and sisters 
together and that gives you so much confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Boldon: ``It's definitely a question of us against them.  
You can never underestimate the importance of that. It's an 
individual sport, but we're a team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller has emerged from the shadow of non-HSI member Marion  
Jones, the world's top female star. Jones was going for four gold 
medals here, but after her 100 victory, settled for bronze in the 
long jump, then pulled up with back spasms and cramps in the 200 
semis and withdrew from the meet. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not just a one-woman show,'' Miller said. ``We'll have a  
pretty good rivalry going next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's other finals, Italy's Fabrizio Mori, who was at  
first disqualified in the semifinals of the men's 400 hurdles and 
then reinstated, won in 47.72, the world's fastest time this year; 
Romania's Gabriela Szabo retained the women's 5,000 title at 
14:41.82, a championship record, and Hongyu Liu led a 1-2 Chinese 
finish in the women's 20-kilometer walk at 1:30:50. 
</P>
<P>
	Mori's victory was protested by the French team, which claimed  
the Italian ran out of his lane and should have been disqualified. 
The protest was rejected. Had it been accepted, France's Stephane 
Diagana, the second-place finisher and Olympic champion, would have 
been the winner. 
</P>
<P>
	There was another protest affecting the third-place finish in  
the women's 200. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamaica's Beverly McDonald was originally awarded the bronze  
ahead of Germany's Andrea Philipp, though both were timed in 22.22. 
After the German's protest, officials decided to give bronze medals 
to both runners. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden's Ludmila Engquist, the inspirational story of the  
championships, continued her remarkable run toward a second 
straight title in the women's 100 hurdles. Engquist, who had 
undergone four chemotherapy treatments for breast cancer and has 
two more remaining, won her semifinal heat at 12.50, the 
second-fastest in the world this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
