<HEADLINE> Pilot Rescued in Lake Michigan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A pilot whose plane dove into Lake Michigan after  
the engine stalled Saturday was rescued by a passing sailboat crew 
who threw him a buoy and motor boat passengers who pulled him 
aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillip Edling, 57, made a distress call to Chicago's Meigs  
Field about 9 a.m., saying his single-engine Piper Cherokee had 
stalled and he couldn't restart it, U.S. Coast Guard Petty Officer 
Howard McCarthy said. 
</P>
<P>
	He had taken off from Chicago's Midway Airport for a tour of the  
lakeshore. 
</P>
<P>
	Edling tried to land the plane on the water, then jumped out,  
McCarthy said. Authorities said no one else was aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is safe. He's shaken up. He's tired and declined medical  
assistance,'' McCarthy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Edling declined to speak to reporters after he was brought  
ashore. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's more worried about getting his plane back,'' said  
Commander Will Knight, a spokesman for the Chicago Fire Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane sank in 25 feet of water.  
</P>
<P>
	The National Transportation Safety Board and Federal Aviation  
Administration were called to investigate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
