<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Reverses Himself on Vouchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A federal judge who blocked a state-funded  
school voucher program this week, sparking turmoil among worried 
parents on the eve of the new school year, has reversed his 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Solomon Oliver Jr. ruled Friday that  
elementary school students who participated in the program last 
year may receive vouchers again this year to attend private 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	However, children new to the program will not be allowed to get  
the tuition grants. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is very unfair to do to children,'' said Dawne Bivins,  
31, who has two daughters signed up for the voucher program. 
</P>
<P>
	Bivins' 10-year-old has received voucher money for three years,  
but her 5-year-old is a first-year participant. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can you give it to one and not the other? How can you do  
that?'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Worried parents of voucher students flooded schools with phone  
calls after Oliver's first ruling, wondering if their children 
could still attend private schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver said the new arrangement, which rolls back a ruling he  
made Tuesday, will last only one semester or until a final judgment 
is reached in a lawsuit claiming the program violates the 
constitutional separation of church and state. 
</P>
<P>
	He set a Dec. 13 trial date for the lawsuit brought by civil  
liberty and other groups. 
</P>
<P>
	About 4,000 students from kindergarten through sixth grade were  
to receive up to $2,500 in tuition vouchers for private schools in 
Cleveland. Court records show that 587 students were expected to 
join the program this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday, Oliver suspended the program until trial, saying the  
program appears to have the ``primary effect of advancing 
religion.'' Most of the 56 private schools that participate are 
religious institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	In his ruling Friday, Oliver said that because the state  
approved funding for this year's voucher program in late July, it 
was inevitable that a court challenge would come in August as 
schools were set to begin. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge's new ruling didn't satisfy some voucher proponents.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm stunned,'' said David Zanotti, chairman of a pro-voucher  
group called The School Choice Committee. ``There's absolutely no 
logic to this decision. Either the program is right or wrong. Why 
do you hang the kids out to dry? 
</P>
<P>
	``He's still jerking around the lives of several hundred  
children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Voucher opponents said they still expect to prevail.  
</P>
<P>
	``The most important thing is that there's nothing that changes  
what he said before -- that he is likely to hold the voucher program 
unconstitutional,'' said Judith Schaeffer, spokeswoman for People 
for the American Way Foundation, a Washington D.C.-based 
anti-voucher group. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just inevitable that those children are going to have to  
leave at some point because they're going to lose this case,'' 
Schaeffer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The state attorney general's office, which has appealed the  
suspension of the program to federal court, said it was still 
deciding whether to file another appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	One pro-voucher group, the Institute for Justice, said it filed  
an immediate appeal of Oliver's latest decision to the 6th U.S. 
Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati, asking that all the voucher 
students be allowed to receive the grants. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4-year-old pilot program, which provides tuition money for  
children of poor families, is the only one of its kind in Ohio. It 
has an $11.2 million budget for this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The voucher schools responded to the first ruling by letting the  
students into class until an appeal was heard or Oliver decided 
whether to let his first decision stand. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
