<DOCNO> APW19990828.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 18:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Said Assessing Abortion Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- A 14-year-old foster girl who says she was raped  
is reportedly expected to travel to Kansas for a late-term abortion 
unless Arizona officials succeed in winning a court ruling to stop 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	There has bee no direct word from the girl herself because of  
foster care confidentiality requirements and a court seal on the 
case. She's said to be about 24 weeks into the pregnancy now, past 
the stage at which abortions are performed in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona Republic quoted sources Saturday as saying Gov. Jane  
Hull had changed direction on Thursday about an appeal and had 
decided to have the girl's competency re-evaluated. But a judge on 
Friday reaffirmed his decision to allow the abortion, the newspaper 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor's office was working feverishly late Friday on a  
second appeal, the Republic said. On Saturday, a spokeswoman for 
the governor refused to discuss whether a second appeal would be 
filed. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, a ward of the state since she was 5 and now a ward of  
Maricopa County Superior Court, told the state she was raped. She 
requested an abortion 14 weeks into the pregnancy but then ran 
away, showing up again only recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Judge William Sargeant authorized the abortion and  
having the girl taken elsewhere for it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
