<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miami, Ohio To Meet in Kickoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Miami guard Richard Mercier wore a  
black T-shirt to an interview session Friday. Printed in bold white 
letters on the front was, ``NCO.'' Under that it said, ``New 'Canes 
Order.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The stakes are high in Sunday's Kickoff Classic, with  
12th-ranked Miami out to prove it has indeed reestablished its old 
winning ``order'' after a bout with NCAA probation and No. 9 Ohio 
State seeking to remain one of the country's elite programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami was 5-6 in 1997, the school's first losing record since  
Howard Schnellenberger's first season in 1979. The Hurricanes were 
unranked and a humdrum 7-3 heading into December last year -- and 
coming off a humiliating 66-13 rout at the hands of Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	But then they ended third-ranked UCLA's unbeaten season and  
hopes for a national title with a 49-45 upset, then followed that 
with a convincing 46-23 win over North Carolina State in a bowl 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Were those just the highlights of an otherwise ordinary season?  
Or are the 'Canes, the dominant college team of the 1980s and early 
'90s, really back? 
</P>
<P>
	``The expectation in previous years was you didn't rebuild, you  
just reloaded,'' said coach Butch Davis, five years into salvaging 
the troubled program he was left by Dennis Erickson. ``The success 
of 12 consecutive Jan. 1 bowl games and four national championships 
really made everybody feel like it was just a matter of showing up 
and playing the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the fans got their eyes opened in '97 when we had the  
first losing season in 20 years. They really started to appreciate 
what these sanctions and probation were all about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scholarships were down, interest was down and so were the  
players' attitudes. Now the Hurricanes are eager to take the next 
step, up to respectability and more national recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	``A win for us Sunday would mean opening eyes, I guess -- opening  
the eyes of the public,'' running back James Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State coach John Cooper recognizes that Miami feels it has  
a point to make. 
</P>
<P>
	``You knew that Miami wasn't going to be down very long,''  
Cooper said. ``There's no question because of the high school 
talent and the kind of program they have down there and the 
coaching staff they had. It was a matter of time until they got 
back to where they should be in college football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State, on the other hand, has finished No. 2 in the country  
two of the last three years. It has churned out NFL products -- four 
in the first round this past year -- and is flush with talent, 
albeit young and inexperienced talent, this time around. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the third time Cooper has taken his team to a  
``preseason bowl'' game, twice to the Kickoff and once the Pigskin 
Classic. He's not shooting for respect or rankings necessarily, but 
preparation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like these early ballgames myself,'' Cooper said. ``I like  
the extra practice time. It may not show up in the first ballgame 
but I think it will definitely help us by the time we get into the 
conference season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper also said he took the game because of the national  
exposure, which widens Ohio State's already wide recruiting base, 
and because each team gets at least $650,000 for playing -- no small 
consideration at Ohio State when you're providing most of the 
revenue for 35 varsity sports. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buckeyes feel they risk a lot. A win helps them maintain the  
respect they already have, but a loss would all but eliminate them 
from the race for the prize they've chased since 1968 -- a national 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in 1986, they had a veteran team led by a first-year  
quarterback and lost 16-10 to Alabama in the Kickoff Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would hurt but I don't think it would be devastating,''  
Cooper said. ``We're not planning to lose, but if we would happen 
to lose, we're not going to fold our tent and act like the season's 
over. I can assure you that's not going to happen. But we're not 
planning on losing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
