<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1939 Boys of Summer Reunite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- The only home they aim to reach these  
days is their own and they are more likely to catch a cold than a 
fly ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, 18 of the 30 boys who played in Little League's  
first season in 1939, had vivid and fond memories of their days on 
the baseball field. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a real camaraderie,'' Peter Smith recalled Friday as  
the men gathered for a reunion on the eve of the Little League 
World Series championship game. ``We couldn't wait for our games. 
</P>
<P>
	Little League was founded in this town with three teams and 30  
players. The Little League World Series for 11- and 12-year-olds 
started in 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, a retired businessman from Dayton, Ohio, played for a  
team in nearby Lycoming. Before Little League his games were played 
on sandlots without the benefit of uniforms and standard fields. 
</P>
<P>
	His brother, Charles, recalled helping league founder Carl Stoz  
measure the basepaths. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember running the bases to see they were right,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Smith, who lives in York, also thinks he and his  
teammates were more driven than their modern counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had more desire to win. We only had 10 players so it was  
the only the best who played,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said it was ``very competitive,'' even more so than today.  
</P>
<P>
	Though for many of the players Little League was the pinnacle of  
their ball playing, Al Yearick went on. 
</P>
<P>
	He signed with the Boston Braves and spent five years in the  
minor leagues. But he recalls his Little League experience as a 
turning point. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was my first opportunity to play with official bats and  
uniforms as opposed to the stuff we played with on the sandlots,'' 
he recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	He thinks today's players have it easier.  
</P>
<P>
	``The equipment is so much better than what we had. The  
biological makeup of the kids is different. They are bigger and 
stronger,'' Yearick said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tom Frazier, a former outfielder who organized the reunion  
with Yearick, said money has changed baseball for the worse, even 
among kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``We used to play every day for fun and that was all. Now they  
want something more,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
