<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Potts Tired of 'Designing Women' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Enjoying the critical success of her latest TV  
show ``Any Day Now,'' Annie Potts is tired of talking about her one 
network ratings hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people ask me about `Designing Women' now,'' she says in  
the Sept. 3 issue of Entertainment Weekly. ``I feel how I think 
James Taylor must feel when he has to play `Fire and Rain' again. 
To tell you the truth, I've moved on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Potts is much more eager to promote ``Any Day Now,'' the show on  
cable's Lifetime channel that reunites two friends, one black and 
one white, after a childhood growing up in the segregationist South 
of the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	She feels blessed to have gotten the job after two failed series  
that followed ``Designing Women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As you get older, there aren't as many worthy suitors,'' said  
Potts, 46. 
</P>
<P>
	She costars with Lorraine Toussaint in the dramatic series  
exploring the depths of childhood friendship and lingering racism 
in America. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
