<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hissou Wins 5000 Gold at Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Salah Hissou won Morocco's second distance  
gold medal at the World Championships today, beating Kenyan 
Benjamin Limo to take the 5,000 meters in a championship record 
time. Belgium's Mohammed Mourhit was third. 
</P>
<P>
	Hissou had set the pace for most of the race, taking that  
position from American Bob Kennedy, who fell back. Hissou outkicked 
all opposition in the final lap to finish in 12 minutes 58.13 
seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Limo clocked a 12:58.72 and the Moroccan-born Mourhit had  
12:58.80 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Daniel Komen of Kenya finished fifth.  
</P>
<P>
	The race missed its biggest star -- Haile Gebrselassie. The  
Ethiopian had won the 10,000-meter world title for the fourth time 
in a row early in the week but is troubled by blisters and sore 
feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Morocco's Hicham El Guerrouj earlier won the 1,500 meters  
</P>
<P>
	Bob Kennedy of the United States immediately set the early pace,  
but was soon overtaken by Hissou, who tried to make a breakthrough 
halfway through the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Komen tried to assert his authority with 1,600 metrs to go but  
Hissou had no problem following in his wake and took the lead again 
going into the final kilometer, with Komen faltering. 
</P>
<P>
 *rac 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
