<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Gun Controls Signed Into Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Outside the medical center where victims of a  
gunman's rampage at a Jewish community center were treated earlier 
this month, Gov. Gray Davis signed into law three bills tightening 
the state's control over guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The laws impose stricter manufacturing standards on cheap  
handguns, require the sale of trigger locks and increase 
regulations at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	With other new laws expanding the state's assault weapons ban  
and limiting residents to purchasing one gun a month, California 
now has the nation's toughest package of gun control laws, Davis 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe in the Second Amendment. But we have been able to  
balance the rights of the Second Amendment in a responsible way to 
protect public safety,'' Davis said Friday outside Providence Holy 
Cross Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics, including the National Rifle Association, said the laws  
will increase illegal gun sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're high on symbolism and low on substance,'' said Steve  
Helsley, state liaison for the NRA. 
</P>
<P>
	California Democrats have pushed for stricter controls for four  
years, but their efforts gained momentum after a 1997 North 
Hollywood shootout between bank robbers and police, the Columbine 
High School tragedy in Littleton, Colo. in April and this month's 
shooting at a Los Angeles Jewish community center. 
</P>
<P>
	The new laws ban the manufacture and sale of poorly made  
handguns and impose stricter manufacturing standards on cheap guns 
commonly referred to as Saturday night specials. 
</P>
<P>
	They also require exhibitors at gun shows to provide more  
information about who will handle the sale of guns, and requires 
minors to be accompanied by a parent. 
</P>
<P>
	Trigger locks must be purchased with each gun, though the lock  
does not have to be put on the weapon. Davis said the locks will 
reduce the number of accidental gun deaths, particularly among 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	All three laws go into effect on Jan. 1.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
