<DOCNO> APW19990828.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 10:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Union Recommends New Boeing Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- After days of pessimistic talk that a strike was  
in the offing, the Machinists union today recommended that 44,000 
Boeing Co. workers accept a new contract with the aerospace 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	A proposal offered by the company early today is ``the best  
contract in the aerospace industry,'' said Bill Johnson, president 
of Machinists District Lodge 751. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace  
Workers union represents 44,000 Boeing workers, who will vote on 
the pact Wednesday -- hours before the current contract expires at 
midnight. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, Johnson said several aspects should please  
members, including retention of a traditional work week, meaning 
workers would continue to be paid overtime for working on weekends. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, the proposal contains no increases in  
member costs for medical benefits, a 25 percent increase in pension 
benefits, and language to help reduce the amount of work contracted 
to outside companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The 44-month contract proposal includes wage increases of 4  
percent in each of the first two years and 3 percent for the 
remainder of the contract period, said union and company officials. 
The average machinist at Boeing earns $40,000 a year, not counting 
benefits or overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Many union members had mentioned job security as a top issue.  
Johnson said the new contract would provide 180 days' notice when 
work is to be contracted out, and would establish a 
union-management committee to try to keep such work in-house. 
</P>
<P>
	The company had announced the proposal early today.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've done our best, and I think we've delivered an agreement  
that our employees ... will at the end of the day find very, very 
attractive,'' Boeing lead negotiator Jerry Calhoun said at a 2 a.m. 
press conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing withdrew a proposed move to a flexible seven-day work  
week that would have cut overtime pay for weekend work. 
</P>
<P>
	Also withdrawn was a proposal to have employees begin paying  
some of the cost of their health insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks came as Boeing is undertaking a massive job cut  
program. From a high of 238,000 in June 1998, Boeing plans to 
reduce its work force to between 185,000 and 195,000 by the end of 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The current contract covers 31,000 workers in Washington state,  
1,400 in Portland, Ore., and 11,600 in Wichita, Kan. Boeing employs 
about 210,000 worldwide. 





</P>
</TEXT>
