<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hurricane Batters Northern Bahamas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- A strengthened Hurricane Dennis battered  
the northern Bahamas on Saturday, tearing up trees and utility 
poles, ripping down buildings under construction and threatening to 
grow even more powerful as it approaches the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters projected Dennis would become a Category 3 storm  
with winds up to 130 mph within 48 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis' core is projected to stay away from shore as it passes  
Florida. But its outer winds could swipe the state on Sunday, and 
it could make landfall as late as Tuesday, most likely somewhere in 
the Carolinas, forecasters said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our forecast shows it about 100 miles offshore'' when it  
passes Florida, said Jerry Jarrell, director of the National 
Hurricane Center in Miami. ``That's significant because we think 
that 50 or 60 mph winds stick out about 100 miles. That suggests 
that they're going to get strong winds and they're really going to 
get some strong surf out of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From hundreds of miles away, Dennis kicked up 8-foot-high waves  
off Florida and North Carolina, delighting surfers but prompting 
officials to put state troopers and the National Guard on alert. 
Hurricane watches and tropical storm warnings were issued along 
hundreds of miles of the eastern seaboard. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. EDT, Dennis was centered 200 miles east-southeast of  
Cape Canaveral in Florida. It had sustained winds of 100 mph, up 
from 80 mph the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm broadened overnight, with hurricane winds extending 40  
miles from its center as it came out of a near-stall and resumed 
its west-northwest track at a crawl close to 6 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrell said he was worried because three projections showed  
Dennis stalling again somewhere between Georgia and the Outer Banks 
with winds of 115 to 130 mph. The storm had hovered for hours 
overnight as it crept alongside the Abaco islands in the Bahamas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The destruction can be a lot worse just because it's hammering  
for a long period of time,'' Jarrell said. ``I think that would be 
the great fear from the stall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The storm had passed the Bahamas by Saturday afternoon. In Grand  
Abaco, a sliver no more than 10 miles wide with a population of 
several thousand, residents told tales of destruction and debris it 
left behind. 
</P>
<P>
	Just back from a drive around Grand Abaco's Marsh Harbour, the  
Rev. Carlton Dorsette said about 70 percent of the walls were down 
on a commercial building under construction and his own house under 
construction was ``totally down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't much rain but lots of wind. I think we probably  
got a direct hit last night,'' he said. ``Lots of trees have 
fallen, power lines are down, a lot of phone lines are damaged, 
cable lines are damaged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A number of boats had gone under in the harbor, but the airport  
looked unscathed, Dorsette said. The Bahamas Air Sea Rescue 
Association said it had heard reports of several boats breaking 
their moorings and smashing onto rocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubert Tate, a fisherman at Sweeting's Cay in the Abacos, said  
the storm damaged banana and other fruit trees, smashing some to 
the ground. It ripped the shingles off some roofs and tore down 
shacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis was expected to dump up to 10 inches of rain and create  
battering waves up to 8 feet above normal that could damage fragile 
coral reefs and strip beaches of sand. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. National Weather Service said projections for Dennis  
``become a bit more uncertain'' after Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	A hurricane watch remained in effect for the east coast of  
Florida from Sebastian Inlet northward to Fernandina Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	People began preparing for the storm, stocking up on supplies  
and lumber. The Federal Emergency Management Agency said it was 
stocking up on water and other necessities at regional centers. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Carolina, Gov. Jim Hodges ordered 1,000 National Guard  
troops and 500 state troopers to prepare for duty, but no decision 
has been made on whether to evacuate people from the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	In North Carolina, 150,000 coastal residents were put on alert,  
as were state troopers and emergency management personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	The South Florida Water Management District lowered water levels  
in canals to lessen the risk of flooding in heavy rains. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 21:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Atler Wins 2 Titles in Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Two days after being edged for the  
national all-around title for the second straight year, Vanessa 
Atler showed why she is one of this nation's best hopes for a 
gymnastics medal in the 2000 Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Atler, 17, won gold in the vault and balance beam as the U.S.  
Gymnastics Championships closed Saturday night. Elise Ray won the 
floor exercise and Jamie Dantzscher and Jennie Thompson tied for 
first on the uneven bars. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt better tonight. I've been out of control all week,''  
Atler said. ``I've been nervous and out of control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atler had a winning score of 9.675 on the vault and 9.775 on the  
beam. Ray scored 9.775 on the floor exercise and Dantzscher and 
Thompson had 9.675s on the uneven bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Atler's victories came 48 hours after her fall on the uneven  
bars prevented her from overtaking Kristen Maloney for the national 
all-around title. Maloney competed in two events Saturday, with her 
best finish a second place in the beam. 
</P>
<P>
	``It helps it feel better, but it does not make up for that,''  
Atler said. ``That's still a big mistake I made, I can't make up 
for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Atler, who won gold medals in vault and floor exercise in the  
1998 Goodwill Games, was the national champion in the floor 
exercise last year and national champion in the vault in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday night, John Roethlisberger had just completed a  
remarkable comeback to the U.S. gymnastics team when he realized 
performing on the floor will be only one of the roles he'll have to 
play on the national squad. 
</P>
<P>
	Roethlisberger, 29, a four-time national champion in the early  
1990s, placed second in the all-around competition Friday night to 
make the national team less than a year after reconstructive 
surgery on his right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to performing, he expects to act as mentor and  
emotional guide for Jason Gatson, one of the nation's top male 
gymnasts who tore a ligament in his right knee Friday night while 
leading the all-around competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson, 18, whose knee buckled as he dismounted from the  
horizontal bar, is expected to have surgery in the next few weeks. 
He flew back to the U.S. Olympic Training Center in Colorado 
Springs, Colo., on Saturday for further examination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought about what my role would be in these four years  
after 1996. Maybe that's one of the things I need to do is to help 
Jason,'' Roethlisberger said. ``I know how he's feeling right now. 
There's not much of a worse feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blaine Wilson captured an unprecedented fourth straight men's  
national all-around title with a nearly flawless performance in 
Friday's finals after Gatson hurt himself on the night's opening 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson's overall score of 115.300 made him the first man to win  
four national titles since Roethlisberger won in 1990, '92, '93 and 
'95. But he was not interested in celebrating -- instead, he was 
thinking of Gatson, his training partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll probably spend most of my time seeing how he's doing,''  
Wilson said. ``Jason obviously is a big link in our team. He will 
be missed, but he will be back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roethlisberger finished second with a score of 111.800. Brett  
McClure was third with 111.500. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson, who finished second in 1996 and '98 and was third in the  
national championships in 1997, held a slim lead over Wilson at the 
start of the all-around finals Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	His right knee buckled as he flew off the high bar, and he fell  
to the side of the mat. After getting iced on the competition 
floor, he was helped to the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson was second in the national all-around competition in 1996  
and '98, losing both times to Wilson. He was third in 1997 behind 
Wilson and Roethlisberger. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury threatens to keep one of the United States' most  
promising male gymnasts out of the Sydney Olympics, though Gatson 
predicted he will return from the injury in time for the 2000 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as I landed, something popped and I just fell to the  
ground, it hurt so bad. I knew something happened, because it was a 
loud pop. My knee just went out on me,'' Gatson said. ``This is 
going to make me stronger. I am going to get it fixed and I am 
going to come back and be on the Olympic team in Sydney.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roethlisberger, who competed with a leg brace in the  
championships and wore three huge ice packs on his legs during a 
post-competition news conference, said he's also confident Gatson 
will be fully healed before the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll be back, no problem, I guarantee,'' Roethlisberger said.  
``It's going to be a tough year for him. But for sure he's going to 
be back up here next year.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 09:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Funding Short for Preservation Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Urban development pushes against Luke  
Brubaker's Pennsylvania farm, making it a prime candidate for 
protection under a program that pays people to keep farming. 
</P>
<P>
	But he may not get anything. Farm preservation programs in most  
states are short of cash and a federal companion program is in 
danger of falling victim to tight congressional spending 
restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	So Brubaker is not sure whether or when he might qualify for  
help for his dairy, poultry and crops farm. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I don't get funding, it would be tempting to sell it for  
development, but I would be disappointed because that is not where 
my heart is,'' Brubaker said. ``One side is basically developed, 
and the other side is pretty well wide open. I can make a 
difference over whether to expand that community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brubaker has applied to sell an easement, or development rights,  
on that tract in Mount Joy, Pa., about 75 miles west of 
Philadelphia and 55 miles north of Baltimore. He already sold an 
easement to protect another farm property farther from the edge of 
sprawl. 
</P>
<P>
	By voluntarily selling easements, farmers continue to own the  
land they till but are barred from pursuing non-farm activities. 
Supporters say the programs help channel sprawl and maintain farm 
clusters needed to ensure a viable agricultural supply and support 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the nonprofit American Farmland Trust, at least 15  
states have easement programs, up from nine in 1990. A handful of 
other states are setting up similar programs, while counties and 
other local governments operate dozens of others. 
</P>
<P>
	The oldest programs are in the Northeast; California, Colorado,  
Kentucky and Michigan are among states that recently established 
easement programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Most face the same problem: Money available through state  
appropriations and bonds does not keep up with demand as farmers 
increasingly seek help resisting the pressures to sell fertile farm 
land to the highest bidder. 
</P>
<P>
	One study estimated that there were at least 2,900 pending  
applications nationwide, and another survey figured that Long 
Island, N.Y., alone needed $180 million. Long Island's Suffolk 
County operates one of the nation's oldest programs but has 
preserved fewer than half of the desired acreage. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are expensive programs, and most of them are not funded  
adequately,'' said Deborah Bowers, who tracks preservation programs 
for the trade newsletter Farmland Preservation Report. ``There's 
lots of development going on, and it's really affecting some of our 
really good, economically strong farming regions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pressures have intensified as more people are willing to  
commute longer distances for what they consider a serene, rural 
lifestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 federal farm law set aside $35 million over six years  
to supplement state and local efforts, but the money lasted only 
three years and met fewer than one in five requests. 
</P>
<P>
	Bills are pending to renew the programs at $55 million a year,  
but even supporters acknowledge that funding is tight. 
</P>
<P>
	Just recently, the Senate had to sidestep spending caps by  
declaring a $7.4 billion farm aid package as ``emergency'' funding. 
The easement program got no funding in pending House and Senate 
spending bills for fiscal 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``The farm economy is in the tank, and a program like this is  
not high on the priority list of lawmakers,'' said Chuck Beretz, 
federal policy manager for American Farmland Trust, a chief 
proponent of easement programs. 
</P>
<P>
	But others argue it's a local issue and should be funded  
locally. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just don't see how the federal government is equipped or  
should be responsible for that,'' said Pete Sepp of the National 
Taxpayers Union. Farm preservation may be laudable, he said, but 
``there are plenty of (local) zoning laws, tax incentives and other 
property-use restrictions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say the limited federal spending raises awareness and  
helps state and local governments create or expand programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can leverage more money than would otherwise be available  
and challenge private groups to match federal funds,'' said Wallace 
Lippincott, land preservation administrator in Baltimore County, 
Md., which surrounds the city of Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	But he warned that every year there is a backlog, ``we could  
lose folks who are in emergency financial situations. They would go 
to the development route, and we would lose that land forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers who participate often use the money to buy new  
equipment, pay taxes or mortgages or save for children's college 
tuition. Unlike zoning and other local ordinances, easement 
commitments are permanent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Zoning can change with an election or with some powerful  
people in the community or someone elected with a different 
mindset,'' said June Mengel, director the Lancaster County, Pa., 
Agricultural Preserve Board. ``We're trying to complement zoning.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 21:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
