<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Voices We Listened to This Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A TV talk show host starts a book club and millions read the  
novels she recommends. 
</P>
<P>
	A baby doctor offers simple advice and his words become a bible  
to parents. 
</P>
<P>
	A president sits before a microphone and his calm authority  
soothes a worried nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Three voices of three generations -- Oprah Winfrey, Dr. Benjamin  
Spock and Franklin D. Roosevelt -- have little in common, except 
this: 
</P>
<P>
	We listened to them.  
</P>
<P>
	The voices of influence in the 20th century are more a cacophony  
than a chorus: Preachers and politicians, journalists and 
humorists, crooners and crusaders, all have permeated the nation's 
consciousness. Along the way, a few have even made history. 
</P>
<P>
	We know their names: Will Rogers, Billy Graham, Walter Winchell.  
</P>
<P>
	We recognize their faces: Martin Luther King, Eleanor Roosevelt,  
Walter Cronkite. 
</P>
<P>
	But more importantly, we remember how their words entertained  
us, guided us, inspired us, forced us to think. 
</P>
<P>
	These were people, for the most part, who were not elected at  
the ballot box, but selected to enter our homes. Their words came 
to us as we read the newspaper, huddled around wooden radios, 
stared at the boob tube or clicked on our computer mouse. 
</P>
<P>
	And we listened. Especially in our most troubled times.  
</P>
<P>
	Though his name is rarely mentioned now, anyone who remembers  
the Depression remembers Father Charles Coughlin. In an era when 
people were homeless and jobless and wanted to know why, the 
priest-turned-broadcaster took to the air waves weekly, spouting 
isolationist, anti-Semitic tirades, attacking bankers and blaming 
the world's problems on capitalism and Communism. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions tuned in, thousands sent money.  
</P>
<P>
	Fast-forward a few decades to the turbulent Vietnam war years.  
Again, millions tuned in, this time to the nightly TV news 
broadcasts of Cronkite, the avuncular anchorman whose graying 
temples and resonant voice helped made him a symbol of moral 
authority. Polls consistently ranked him among the country's most 
trusted men. 
</P>
<P>
	We listened as Cronkite, returning from a reporting trip in  
Vietnam in 1968, declared the United States ``mired in a 
stalemate.'' Negotiation, he said, was the only rational course. 
</P>
<P>
	The words shook President Lyndon Johnson. ``If we have lost  
Walter, we have lost the country,'' he reportedly said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the first time in American history that a war had been  
declared over by a commentator,'' author David Halberstam wrote 
years later. 
</P>
<P>
	``What made that powerful was up to that point he had not  
committed himself,'' Garry Wills, the Pulitzer Prize-winning 
historian says of Cronkite. ``He was expending political capital he 
had accrued over the decades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout this century, we listened to political leaders, whose  
words sometimes defined pivotal moments in history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every crisis produces a great voice,'' says Marshall Fishwick,  
a professor who specializes in popular culture at Virginia Tech 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	FDR revolutionized politics and radio with his ``fireside  
chats,'' in which he reassured and rallied a nation through the 
bleak years of the Depression and World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to win the war and we are going to win the peace  
that follows,'' he vowed in a broadcast two days after Pearl Harbor 
was bombed. ``And in the difficult hours of this day -- through dark 
days that may be yet to come -- we will know that the vast majority 
of the members of the human race are on our side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Decades later, another president, John F. Kennedy, captivated  
the nation with his wit, eloquence and Boston-starched voice as he 
spoke of new frontiers and of a ``torch ... passed to a new 
generation of Americans born in this century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1960s also brought forth voices of change, from Malcolm X,  
with his fiery black nationalist rhetoric, to King, with his 
impassioned cry for racial equality and an end to intolerance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must learn to live together as brothers or perish together  
as fools,'' King, the preacher, thundered as blood flowed in the 
streets during the civil rights battles. 
</P>
<P>
	His words still echo 31 years after his assassination, says Char  
Miller, history department chairman at Trinity University in San 
Antonio, Texas. ``What we remember are those extraordinary speeches 
that called into question the fundamental errors of American 
society and did so in a language that has an edge to it,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the way we listen has changed -- we've progressed from a  
scratchy ``wireless'' to 24-hour cable channels -- Miller says there 
has been a remarkable consistency in those we tune in. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of what makes somebody famous or infamous is they speak  
directly to the needs of a large number of Americans,'' he says. 
``They pose a question that's been in our heads that we haven't 
articulated, or they provide an answer to a question that's been 
kicking around a long time and we haven't figured out a way to 
solve it. ... We use them as a mirror.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes they're guides for everyday life.  
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Spock told us how to care for our children; Emily Post, how  
to mind our manners; Dale Carnegie, how to win friends and 
influence people; Norman Vincent Peale, how to be a positive 
thinker. And Ann Landers is still telling us how to cope with the 
in-laws, the boss, the neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without question, Ann Landers must have a treasure trove of  
letters that would introduce us to the American psyche and changes 
in society more than anybody else I know,'' says Joe Boskin, 
director of the urban studies program at Boston University. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes, voices are spiritual guides.  
</P>
<P>
	When radio was in its infancy, the airwaves crackled with Aimee  
Semple McPherson's talk of miracles, heaven and salvation. Decades 
later, when television first entered our living rooms, Archbishop 
Fulton Sheen became not just a voice, but a face, the first to 
combine the force of religion and a mesmerizing new medium. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon dozens of television ministers followed, but none had the  
longevity and legitimacy of the Rev. Billy Graham, whose crusades 
around the globe were beamed into millions of homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever a president's in trouble, they trot him out,'' Miller  
says. ``He's a person who can make things all right -- just by his 
presence, he gives you a kind of benediction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes a president need offer only himself.  
</P>
<P>
	President Reagan's voice, cultivated as a broadcaster before he  
entered politics, delivered gentle humor and sunny visions of 
morning in America that helped solidify his reputation as ``the 
great communicator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Reagan often joked about himself, we liked hearing others  
poke fun at politics itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Politics has become so expensive that it takes a lot of money  
even to be defeated.'' The grumbling of a presidential candidate at 
century's end? Nope. The words of Will Rogers, who combined 
homespun humor with a serious populist message. 
</P>
<P>
	Populism spoke to us, too, in pen and ink, which served as  
America's voice early in the century. 
</P>
<P>
	There were muckraking journalists Ida Tarbell and Upton  
Sinclair, who took on industry, the great iconoclast H.L. Mencken 
and press lord William Randolph Hearst, whose ``penny press'' could 
ignite a war with Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio gave us a new breed of celebrity journalists, none more  
famous than Edward R. Murrow, the world-weary, chain-smoking 
foreign correspondent whose eyewitness accounts (``This -- is 
London'') from rooftops as bombs fell brought the war into our 
living rooms. Later, on television, Murrow helped bring down Sen. 
Joseph McCarthy at the height of the Red Scare. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio also gave us Lowell Thomas, our guide to news fronts  
around the world, and Paul Harvey, who brought us home again with 
the words of a cracker-barrel philosopher and cadences of America's 
heartland. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a pattern to my broadcasts, it is mostly to report  
the things that interest me -- what people want to know and what 
people need to know in a blend that changes every day,'' says 
Harvey, 80, whose voice is still heard on more than 1,300 stations. 
``So much of what we report as news is frivolous, all color and no 
beer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But entertainment has its place, too. Millions tuned in to  
George Burns and Jack Benny for laughs, Sinatra and Elvis for 
music, Johnny Carson and his late-night successors for monologues 
with social and political commentary cloaked in one-liners. 
</P>
<P>
	And, of course, there was Walter Winchell, whose breathless,  
staccato tidbits about the private lives of politicians and movie 
stars pioneered the gossip industry that is a staple at century's 
end. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gossip,'' he once said, ``is the art of saying nothing in a  
way that leaves practically nothing unsaid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At century's end, the range of voices we listen to has  
broadened, especially in recent decades as racial and gender 
barriers have fallen. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are whole parts of America represented or addressed that  
weren't before,'' says Wills, the historian. ``Women, minorities, 
gays -- we have political voices addressing their concerns. We 
didn't have that 50 years ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were trailblazers, of course.  
</P>
<P>
	Eleanor Roosevelt, both as a first lady and after, lectured and  
wrote, championing the causes of women, the poor and oppressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Real prosperity can only come when everybody prospers,'' she  
once wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Feminist Betty Friedan challenged us to reconsider our notions  
of a woman's role. ``Who knows what women can be when they are 
finally free to be themselves?'' she wrote in ``The Feminine 
Mystique.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, who could have imagined decades ago that millions of TV  
viewers would watch a woman TV host dish about her weight, then run 
out to buy the pajamas she wears, the cookbook she endorses, the 
novels she reads? 
</P>
<P>
	``Oprah is someone who most people could identify with,'' says  
Brian Lavelle, of Loyola University in Chicago. ``She has an air of 
truthfulness and candor about her. She's a true voice for many, 
many women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With so many media outlets, the din has grown and more people  
today have a microphone -- radio shock jocks, real jocks talking 
sports, movie stars pontificating about politics, 
politician-pundits trying to drown each other out. 
</P>
<P>
	The result: Fewer voices dominate the microphone, says Paul  
Levinson, a professor of communications and media studies at 
Fordham University. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the 20th century ends,'' he says, ``rather than one person  
on stage that everyone is paying attention to, there are a lot of 
people standing in a lot of different corners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And one of those still standing -- Paul Harvey -- wonders how long  
the clamor will go on. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the multiplicity of media, we're all sitting on the edge  
of our chairs every day,'' he says. ``I think there will come a 
time, if we're not careful, that we'll all be ignored.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
