<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Authorities Rule Against BNP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Banque Nationale de Paris' plans to create Europe's  
biggest bank ended in failure today when French banking regulators 
ruled that it cannot keep its stake in Societe Generale, its 
unwilling takeover target. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling, which came after an 11-hour meeting of the Committee  
of Credit and Investment Institutions, culminated a six-month 
banking battle, France's most brutal takeover fight ever. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP ``doesn't hold in a patent manner an effective power of  
control over Societe Generale,'' the committee said in a statement. 
``In these conditions, the committee decided ... not to authorize 
BNP to hold a stake representing 31.8 percent of voting rights in 
Societe Generale,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	The much-awaited decision is a blow for those who sought to  
create a French banking ``champion,'' but a victory for those who 
say the market should have the last word. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of the ruling, BNP ends up with Paribas, the smaller  
of its targets in a three-way merger attempt -- and the one it never 
really wanted. And Societe Generale is now vulnerable to a foreign 
takeover, which the French government wanted to avoid. 
</P>
<P>
	In its first reaction, BNP said in a statement that it will now  
focus on its merger with Paribas. The bank can appeal the ruling 
with France's highest administrative court, the Council of State, 
but said it was unlikely to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP also said a new offer for Societe Generale was unlikely.  
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale said it ``registered with satisfaction'' the  
ruling by banking regulators. The bank also thanked its 
shareholders for their trust and loyalty. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling comes amid intensified banking merger activity  
elsewhere. On Monday, Germany's Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank 
raised the possibility of a full merger by confirming a retail 
banking link. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, BNP launched a twin, $37 billion hostile takeover bid  
for Societe Generale and Paribas, which were in the midst of a 
friendly merger. BNP's three-way merger would have created a 
banking giant with more than $1 trillion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	While BNP won control of Paribas, it garnered only a 37.1  
percent stake -- and 31.8 percent of voting rights -- in Societe 
Generale, leaving the outcome with the regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee had said it would intervene in the stock market  
battle if a bank failed to gain 50.01 percent of the voting rights 
in its target. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling will be popular with Societe Generale employees, who  
had demonstrated Friday in front of the Bank of France, saying they 
feared the merger would lead to wage and job cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP had claimed it had enough shares for effective control over  
Societe Generale, which vigorously opposed BNP, saying its hostile 
suitor would not have the authority to make major decisions for the 
bank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
