<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins Sign No. 1 Draft Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Pitcher Josh Beckett on Saturday became the last  
of this summer's first-round draft picks to sign a pro contract, 
getting a four-year, $7 million deal from the Florida Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett, picked No. 2 overall in June, will make his debut in  
the Fall Instructional League. 
</P>
<P>
	The 19-year-old right-hander had planned to start classes at  
Blinn Junior College in Texas next week if there was no deal. If 
that had happened, the Marlins would have lost his rights and 
Beckett would have become eligible for the draft again next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am so pleased and glad that this deal got done,'' Beckett  
said. ``It was a long process, but now I look forward to playing 
baseball for the Marlins. It's hard to put into words how happy I 
am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett, who will be placed on the Marlins' 40-man roster, got a  
signing bonus of $3,625,000. His contract runs through the 2002 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a long but amicable negotiation, and we feel we have  
signed one of the most talented pitchers to come through the draft 
in several years,'' Marlins general manager Dave Dombrowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett was the first high school right-hander taken in the top  
two picks since Bill Gullickson in 1979. He was 13-2 with an 0.39 
ERA and 178 strikeouts in 89 innings this season at Spring High 
School in suburban Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins announced the signing at the Astrodome prior to  
their game at Houston on Saturday night. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
