<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indiana Newspaper Suspends TV Writer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indianapolis Star and News has suspended  
and reassigned its television writer for plagiarizing a story 
written by a writer at another newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Hall admitted he made a ``stupid mistake'' and received a  
three-week, unpaid suspension. When he returns, he will be assigned 
to reporting duties that do not involve opinion writing, according 
to a statement by Executive Editor Frank Caperton. 
</P>
<P>
	``He also has been warned that if any further lapses in honesty  
come to light he will be dismissed,'' Caperton said in the 
statement, which was printed on the front page of today's editions 
and posted on the newspaper's Web site Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall's story was not published but ``he submitted it for  
publication with every intention of having it appear in the 
paper,'' Caperton said today. He said there were no indications 
that this had happened in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone call by The Associated Press to Hall was not  
returned Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the statement, Hall, who has been a television writer at the  
newspaper for 13 years, apologized. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of time pressures, I made a stupid mistake and  
violated a sacred law of our profession,'' he said. ``I apologize 
to our readers and my family, co-workers and friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plagiarism was discovered when an editor at the newspaper  
noticed a story submitted by Hall was similar to one written by a 
television writer at another newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	No details were given about Hall's story, and the other  
newspaper and writer were not identified. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsroom staffs of the Star and News merged in 1995 and the  
News is due to close Oct. 1. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
