<HEADLINE> Wife of Kans. State Coach Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Nancy Bennett, wife of Kansas State  
defensive coordinator Phil Bennett, died Saturday of injuries 
sustained when she was struck by lightning over two weeks ago while 
jogging during a violent thunderstorm. She was 41. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett had been in intensive care at Mercy Hospital since she  
was injured Aug. 11 and never regained consciousness. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides her husband, she leaves two young children, Sam, 11, and  
Maddie, 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett, who worked as a registered nurse while following her  
husband through his various coaching jobs, was struck by lightning 
near the Kansas State campus. Bennett, worried about his wife being 
out in the storm, arrived on the scene just as she was being put in 
the ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett, who has missed practices to be with his wife, said in a  
statement issued through the school that he was grateful for 
thousands of people who had expressed their compassion and concern 
through the ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett joined the Kansas State staff in January and was named  
defensive coordinator in February. 
</P>
<P>
	He came to Kansas State from Oklahoma, where he had coached the  
secondary. He also coached at Texas Christian, Texas A&AMP;M, LSU, 
Purdue and Iowa State. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett, 43, played defensive end at Texas A&AMP;M from 1974-77.  
</P>
<P>
	Other survivors include Nancy Bennett's parents, Dr. and Mrs.  
O.T. Harris of Texas, two sisters and two brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	Services are scheduled for 1 p.m. Monday at the First United  
Methodist Church in Manhattan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
