<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Union Recommends New Boeing Deal  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- After days of pessimistic talk that a strike was  
in the offing, the Machinists union today recommended that 44,000 
Boeing workers accept a new contract with the aerospace company. A 
proposal offered by the company early today is ``the best contract 
in the aerospace industry,'' said Bill Johnson, president of 
Machinists District Lodge 751. The workers will vote on the pact 
Wednesday. Johnson said several aspects of the deal should please 
members, including keeping a traditional work week, so workers will 
continue to be paid overtime for working on weekends. 

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Dennis Grows Stronger  
</P>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis grew stronger today as  
it blows through the Bahamas and chugs toward the U.S. eastern 
seaboard. With Dennis intensifying and slowing down at the same 
time, U.S. forecasters say the storm is expected to stay offshore 
as it moves past Florida, with landfall on the mainland possibly 
late Monday or Tuesday somewhere in the Carolinas. From hundreds of 
miles away, Dennis kicked up 8-foot-high waves off Florida and 
North Carolina, prompting officials to put state troopers and the 
National Guard on alert. 

</P>
<P>
	East Timor Gangs Defy U.N.  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Defying U.N. demands for peace in the  
days before a referendum on independence, militia gangs roamed 
unchecked through East Timor's capital today, sending hundreds of 
people fleeing in terror. The anti-independence gangs' sweep 
through the dusty streets of eastern Dili followed days of violence 
that have left at least 10 dead across the troubled territory. 
Residents of the former Portuguese colony are to vote Monday in a 
historic U.N.-supervised referendum on whether to break away from 
Indonesia. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Planes Strike Iraq Radar Sites  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- U.S. warplanes struck Iraqi air defense  
systems with bombs and missiles today after being targeted and 
fired on by the Iraqi forces, the U.S. military said. U.S. fighter 
planes dropped precision-guided bombs on a military radar site 
south of the city of Mosul, the U.S. European Command said. They 
also fired missiles at an installation that targeted the planes 
with missile-guidance radar. 

</P>
<P>
	Clintons House-Hunt in N.Y.  
</P>
<P>
	WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- The First Family ended their island  
vacation today and stepped into a silver Suburban for another day 
of house hunting in Westchester County. President Clinton brushed 
aside a question about whether he and his wife, Hillary Rodham 
Clinton, were close to buying. ``Some place nice and airy that will 
make Hillary happy -- that's what I want,'' he said today. Later, 
the Clintons and their daughter, Chelsea, will continue on to the 
Hamptons for fund-raisers this weekend. 

</P>
<P>
	French Bank Appeal Unlikely  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Banque Nationale de Paris is likely to scrap its  
attempts to create Europe's biggest bank after French regulators 
killed its hostile bid for Societe Generale, ordering it to 
relinquish its stake in the bank. BNP can appeal the order to 
France's highest administrative court, but it said in a statement 
today that an appeal is ``highly unlikely.'' The ruling marks a big 
victory for the market in France where the government often plays a 
big role in regulating the economy: The regulators didn't force the 
merger, even though the government wanted it to go through. 

</P>
<P>
	Lewis-Holyfield Rematch May Be Set  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- After months of haggling, the heavyweight title  
unification rematch between Lennox Lewis and Evander Holyfield is 
finally set, according to a spokesman for promoter Don King. ``The 
fight is a go for Nov. 13,'' said Greg Fritz, of Don King 
Productions. The official announcement will be made at a news 
conference Tuesday. The fight will be held at the Thomas &AMP; Mack 
center on the UNLV campus. Holyfield and Lewis fought to a 
controversial draw March 13 in a fight many ringsiders felt was won 
by Lewis. 

</P>
<P>
	Arab Bodybuilders Stripped of Medals  
</P>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Six bodybuilders were stripped of their  
medals at the Arab Games today after testing positive for 
muscle-building steroids. Substances that showed up in the tests 
were Nandrolone, Metenolone, Stanozolol and testasterone, according 
to Reda Kazem, head of the Arab Games Doping Committee. The 
drug-control committee targeted bodybuilders because the Arab Union 
of Bodybuilders, preparing for the Sydney Olympics, wanted to show 
that its competitors were clean, Kazem said. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
