<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Confirms Tripp Tapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELLICOTT CITY, Md. (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky has confirmed the  
authenticity of taped conversations secretly recorded by Linda 
Tripp, according to court documents filed by state prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	A Maryland grand jury indicted Mrs. Tripp on July 30 on two  
felony counts, charging that she illegally tape-recorded the former 
White House intern on Dec. 22, 1997 and disclosed the contents of 
the conversation to Newsweek magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 16, Ms. Lewinsky listened to copies of tapes made by  
Tripp in October 1997, and confirmed the identities of the voices 
on them, state prosecutors said Thursday. Mrs. Tripp testified that 
she taped several conversations with Lewinsky in late 1997, even 
after an attorney told her it was illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors also disclosed that the copies were provided to the  
state by Lucianne Goldberg, a New York literary agent. Ms. 
Goldberg, who testified in Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's 
investigation last November, said she urged Mrs. Tripp to start 
taping. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp turned over the tapes to Starr, triggering the  
investigation into Ms. Lewinsky's affair with President Clinton. In 
return, she received a federal grant of immunity from prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for Mrs. Tripp have asked a judge to dismiss the  
charges, arguing state prosecutors improperly relied on her 
immunized testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	State Prosecutor Stephen Montanarelli has denied that his office  
used information gathered by federal sources. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
