<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fires May Show Need To Thin Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Critics say the more than 20 major  
wildfires charring brush and timber on thousands of acres in five 
western states demonstrate the need to thin forests to prevent 
catastrophic fires. 
</P>
<P>
	The blazes have burned more than 190,000 acres as of Friday.  
Michael Paparian, a Sierra Club representative, said the wildfires 
underscore the need for active forest management. 
</P>
<P>
	Years of aggressive firefighting have allowed brush to flourish  
that, left alone, would have been cleared away naturally by 
wildfires, he said. That brush now fuels wildfires, making them so 
hot they kill large trees that otherwise would likely survive. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way the forests have been managed up to now can lead to  
more catastrophic fires than using a more rational approach,'' 
Paparian said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Bischel, president of the California Forestry Association,  
which represents the timber industry, agreed the forests need 
thinning. However, timber companies want the process to include 
more logging than the environmental groups support. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, firefighters have carved bare-earth control lines around  
some of the smaller lightning-sparked fires so they can focus on 
battling uncontrolled blazes. More than half the fires were in 
California. Others were in Nevada, Oregon, Washington and Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've been able to handle the new starts and get a better  
handle on what they're already fighting. Things are looking better 
today,'' Janelle Smith of the National Interagency Fire Center in 
Boise, Idaho, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wildfires temporarily chased hundreds of residents from their  
homes in California and Nevada early this week but have burned few 
homes. There were no mandatory evacuations in effect Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 10,000 firefighters with 700 fire engines and scores  
of helicopters and air tankers battled the wildfires Friday. 
Several were sparked by lightning, and some have been burning since 
last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	In California, fires have burned tens of thousands of acres in  
the Shasta-Trinity, Lassen, Klamath, Plumas, Modoc, Stanislaus and 
Angeles national forests. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters in Nevada battled a 7,400-acre grass fire 70 miles  
northwest of Winnemucca, a cluster of fires totaling 36,000 acres 
north of Reno, and a 2,000 acre-fire near Carson City. 
</P>
<P>
	In Oregon, a 30,000-acre brush fire burned in the Sheldon-Hart  
National Wildlife Refuge. Firefighters in Washington battled a 
350-acre blaze on the Colville Indian Reservation. And in Texas, 
fires burned 1,500 acres northwest of Lampasas and 580 acres near 
Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Wildfires earlier this week in Montana and Idaho had been  
brought under control by Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists and loggers say the government should conduct  
more controlled burns and cutting to clear undergrowth that fuels 
wildfires. But government officials said the answer wouldn't be 
simple. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no magic solution to the condition of the forests,''  
said U.S. Forest Service spokesman Matt Mathes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our forests have gotten into their current state during 150  
years of human manipulation,'' he said. ``It will take us many 
years of thinning and prescribed burning to get the forest back to 
where it would have been if humans had not intervened.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0093 </DOCNO>
