<HEADLINE> Stabbing Suspect Was Tossed Off Bus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A day before three people were stabbed aboard  
an Amtrak train in Ohio, the man charged in the knifing attack was 
removed from a Greyhound bus in Illinois as an unruly passenger, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron Hall, 41, of Ontario, Calif., is being held on three  
counts of attempted murder for the Thursday assault outside of 
Cleveland. During Wednesday's bus disturbance in Princeton, Ill., 
Hall was not arrested and no one was hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	However, when Illinois State Police checked Hall for weapons,  
they found a pocketknife with a 2 1/2-inch blade, which they allowed 
him to keep. Olmsted Township Police Chief Dennis McCafferty said 
it apparently is the weapon used in the attack on the Amtrak train 
outside Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``The suspect claimed the same thing there as he did here, that  
he was afraid of gang members who had a gun,'' McCafferty said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald Piszczek, appointed as Hall's attorney, was unavailable  
to comment Friday, his secretary said. 
</P>
<P>
	Illinois State Police Master Sgt. Lincoln Hampton said Hall had  
boarded a bus in Iowa and was headed to Chicago. He said that on 
Interstate 80 near Princeton, 100 miles west of Chicago, the bus 
driver notified a Greyhound dispatcher that a passenger complained 
he was being threatened by four other passengers with a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	A patrol trooper stopped the bus and searched the four  
passengers Hall had pointed out and then searched Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Hampton said no gun was found, and the passengers denied having  
threatened Hall. When Hall was searched, a pocketknife was found, 
but he was allowed to keep it because carrying a small pocketknife 
is legal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then the driver asked that Mr. Hall not be returned to bus.  
Greyhound arranged for him to continue on another bus from 
Princeton,'' Hampton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanyo said Hall caught the Amtrak train in Chicago and was  
headed to New York. After the stabbings, in court, Hall told 
reporters he was trying to disarm an attacker and acted in 
self-defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall is accused of stabbing two Amtrak employees and a passenger  
on the Lake Shore Limited outside Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Two victims remained hospitalized today. Amtrak employee Michael  
Dwyer, 52, was in serious condition with a head wound. The 
passenger, John Henry Crotty, 36, of Butler, Ind., was in stable 
condition with stab wounds to his cheek and jaw, hospital officials 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
