<DOCNO> APW19990828.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 15:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pedroso Wins Third Long Jump Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Indoors or outdoors, it doesn't matter for  
Ivan Pedroso. The Cuban long jumper has won seven World 
Championship titles since 1993. It's the Olympics in which he's 
still winless. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedroso added his third straight outdoor title Saturday,  
overcoming muscle problems to soar 28 feet, 1 inch and earn the 
gold medal ahead of the home favorite Yago Lamela. 
</P>
<P>
	In a stirring competition, Lamela jumped 27-6 3/4. Gregor Cankar  
gave Slovenia its first World Championship medal in history by 
taking the bronze at 27-5 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Since he fouled out of the 1993 outdoor championships, Pedroso  
hasn't lost in the worlds. 
</P>
<P>
	But he's had no such luck in the Olympics. In 1992 at Barcelona,  
he just missed out, finishing fourth as a 19-year-old newcomer. At 
Atlanta four years later, Pedroso was coming off hamstring surgery 
and reached the final, only to finish last. 
</P>
<P>
	``The great goal for every athlete is to win the Olympic gold  
medal. I was too young in Barcelona and I was unlucky to get 
injured before Atlanta. I hope to have better luck in Sydney next 
year,'' Pedroso said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Atlanta, he has largely dominated the long jump and, at  
26, is young enough to have bigger goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from the Olympic gold, there is also the matter of Mike  
Powell's world record of 29-4 1/2 set eight years ago. Pedroso leaped 
29-4 3/4 in a meet at Sestriere, Italy in 1995, but a judge standing 
too close to the wind meter cast doubt on the legality of the jump, 
which was never recognized as a record by the International Amateur 
Athletic Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	He also had a narrow foul on a 29-7 1/2 jump in the 1995  
Pan-American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Pedroso was just concerned with getting into the  
top eight in the first three series and hoping to save his best 
efforts for the last three jumps. 
</P>
<P>
	But a twinge in his muscle forced Pedroso to skip two of his  
last three jumps, and cut short his fifth attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	His third leap, which came close to his season-leading 28-2 3/4,  
was good enough for the gold. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my first two jumps, I was just trying to make the last  
eight. But my coach told me that I was too slow in my approach and 
I stepped it up in the third.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in good shape before the competition and I felt I could  
go 28-6 1/2 or more. But then I started feeling muscle problems and I 
couldn't really jump any better,'' Pedroso said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamela, 22, leaped 27-4 1/2 in his first effort, lifted by the  
partisan capacity crowd at the Estadio Olimpico. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lamela and the crowd put some pressure on me, but I knew I had  
the gold after going over 8.50 (27-10 3/4),'' Pedroso said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamela was in danger of losing the silver when the 24-year-old  
Slovenian hit 27-5 1/4 in the fourth series. But the Spaniard, who 
also took silver behind Pedroso in this winter's indoors, 
immediately replied with a 27-6 3/4 effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to get a big jump at the start. I was very aggressive  
and I risked a lot,'' said Lamela, who fouled on his second and 
third jumps. ``It was a great honor to compete in front of the 
Spanish crowd, but maybe I got carried away by all the support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every time Lamela came up to jump, the crowd broke into a  
deafening shout of ``Yago! Yago!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cankar put in the most consistent series of his career, fouling  
only once and his worst jump was 26-5 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had some problems in my approach. Even my best jump was not  
perfect and I felt I was capable of doing more tonight,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
