<DOCNO> APW19990828.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 10:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Activity Trays Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 100,000 activity trays and toy nets are  
being recalled following reports that young children have choked on 
suction cups used to attach them to surfaces. 
</P>
<P>
	The Consumer Product Safety Commission recalled the Stroller  
Snack and Activity Trays, Bathtime Activity Trays and Bathtime Toy 
Netting -- sold by Graco Children's Products and Children on the Go. 
The federal agency said children can easily detach the suction cups 
and choke on them. 
</P>
<P>
	Graco has received reports of four choking incidents, one each  
in Wisconsin and Ohio and two in New York, commission spokeswoman 
Nychelle Fleming said Friday. In the Ohio incident, the suction cup 
was dislodged from the throat of a 7-month-old. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled items can be used with toys from the Mix 'N Move  
line and attached to strollers, bath tub tiles or other smooth 
surfaces. They were sold nationwide at discount, department and toy 
stores from January 1998 until this month for $10 to $15 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers should call (800) 446-1366 to receive a free repair  
kit that will permanently attach the suction cups to the trays. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 12:45:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Focuses on Kosovo Revenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STARA CIKATOVA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ex-Balkan troubleshooter  
Richard Holbrooke, in Kosovo on his first trip abroad as America's 
new U.N. ambassador, toured a mass grave site Saturday and 
declared, ``we need to remember what brought us here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke went to Stara Cikatova soon after his helicopter  
landed in Pristina, the provincial capital. The town 12 miles west 
of Pristina has a mass grave believed to contain bodies of men, 
women and children killed by the Serbs early this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston-based Physicians for Human Rights began exhuming  
bodies more than a month ago and has found about 130 so far at 
three separate but neighboring sites. But the group has problems 
identifying the bodies because of their advanced state of 
decomposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke spent about 45 minutes at the mass grave area, also  
visiting a ridge where the victims were allegedly lined up and 
shot, and talked to several villagers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not learning anything here that isn't in previous  
accounts,'' he told reporters. ``But to be in the physical presence 
of the events, that is different. While we are trying to forge a 
peace, we need to remember what brought us here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. diplomat is due to spend three days in Kosovo before  
going to Bosnia and Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in Pristina, he said he had come to the region at the  
request of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright because ``the 
U.N. is being tested in Kosovo as it has never been tested before, 
with responsibilities greater than ever before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he planned to meet with Bernard Koucher, the chief U.N.  
administrator of Kosovo; senior commanders of the NATO-led 
peacekeeping force; Hashim Thaci, leader of the rebel Kosovo 
Liberation Army; and moderate Kosovo Albanian leader Ibrahim 
Rugova. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke's visit is filled with symbolism.  
</P>
<P>
	He helped broker the 1995 Dayton accords that ended the 3 1/2-year  
war in Bosnia and later served as President Clinton's special envoy 
to Yugoslavia on Kosovo, which is a province in the Yugoslav 
federation's dominant republic of Serbia. He failed to persuade 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to compromise, and 78 days of 
NATO bombing followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke comes to Kosovo amid widespread ethnic violence,  
mostly against Serbs by majority ethnic Albanians seeking to avenge 
the 18-month Serb crackdown that left about 10,000 people dead and 
hundreds of thousands temporary refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	International peacekeepers in Kosovo have been unable to stop a  
wave of revenge attacks by the ethnic Albanians -- 90 percent of 
Kosovo's prewar population of 2.1 million -- against Serbs, Gypsies 
and other non-Albanian groups. 
</P>
<P>
	In an example of the tension, a strong explosion before  
Holbrooke arrive rocked downtown Pristina, damaging a communist-era 
monument to ethnic harmony. Nobody was hurt in the pre-dawn blast. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Friday, international peacekeepers found the corpses of two  
women. One, a 60-year-old Serb woman, was found in the southwestern 
city of Prizren in central Kosovo. The other, unidentified and in 
her late 30s, apparently was beaten to death. No other details were 
given. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
