<DOCNO> APW19990828.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 16:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heyns, Krayzelburg Break Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Records don't stand a chance in the  
pool that will be the site for the next Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	South Africa's Penny Heyns and American Lenny Krayzelburg were  
the latest to topple world marks Saturday in the Pan Pacific swim 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns broke her eighth breaststroke world record in 11 swims and  
Krayzelburg set his third backstroke mark of the meet in special 
50-meter time trials organized around the main program. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve records have been broken -- at least one in seven straight  
days -- in the pool that will be used for the 2000 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns set up a 50 time trial during the morning heats and  
Krayzelburg did the same in tackling the 50 backstroke at the end 
of the finals session. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns' time of 30.83 seconds beat her 30.95 set in the Goodwill  
Games at New York last August. Krayzelburg's 24.99 beat the 25.13 
set by fellow American Jeff Rouse before the event was given world 
record status two years ago by FINA, the governing body. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked about it a couple of days ago and they pretty much  
told me it was up to me,'' Krayzelburg said. ``I thought about it 
after the 100 when I went out in 25.9, and that was pretty close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	South Africa enjoyed a double celebration as Brendon Dedekind  
edged Olympic silver medalist Gary Hall Jr. and world champion Bill 
Pilczuk in the 50 free to claim the country's first gold by a male 
swimmer in the PanPacs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I only breathed once,'' the exhausted Dedekind said. ``I  
usually breathe twice, but I saw Gary there so I thought I better 
only breathe once.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dedekind's 22.06 matched the fifth-fastest by a man with  
Dutchman Pieter van den Hoogenband, who had a 22.06 in the European 
Championships earlier this month. Hall was clocked in 22.26 and 
Pilczuk finished in 22.52. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Klim, the 100 butterfly world record-holder, couldn't  
improve his time of 52.15 but was happy just to beat fellow 
Australian Geoff Huegill and take a fourth gold of the meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Klim, the world champion, finished second and was behind until  
the last few strokes before touching first in 52.49, ahead of 
Huegill's 52.51. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the plan for me tonight, to finish strong in the last  
six strokes,'' said Klim, who also won the 100 freestyle and two 
relays. ``That's where I thought it was going to be won and that's 
how it turned out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American Brooke Bennett continued her reign in the 800  
freestyle, cruising to a victory in a personal-best 8:25.06, 
10th-best in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett won the gold medal in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and  
followed with victories in the 1997 PanPacs and last year's world 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's World Student Games champion Tomoko Hagiwara held off  
national record holder Miki Nakao in the 200 backstroke for the 
country's second gold. Mai Nakamura, who won a gold in the 100, 
failed to reach the 200 final. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-time Olympic 1,500-meter champion Kieren Perkins might have  
competed in his last international race after failing to qualify 
for Sunday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	The world record holder, whose campaign was derailed by illness,  
was beaten by Craig Stevens in Saturday's first heat. Perkins and 
Stevens then watched world champion Grant Hackett better their 
times in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	Perkins' time of 15:28.43 was almost 47 seconds slower than the  
world record of 14:41.66 he set in the 1994 Commonwealth Games. It 
was his worst time in nine years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
