<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Union Recommends New Boeing Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Machinists union is urging its 44,000 Boeing  
Co. workers to accept the company's new contract offer, which one 
union official called the best in the aerospace industry. 
</P>
<P>
	After months of strike threats, Boeing officials relented on two  
of the most contentious issues -- job security and a company plan to 
end overtime pay for weekend work. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe this contract is the best contract in the aerospace  
industry,'' Bill Johnson, president of Machinists District Lodge 
751, told union members Saturday morning. Though he added, ``I wish 
we could have negotiated better language on job security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow union members who stopped by the Seattle headquarters to  
read the 44-month contract offer were reacting positively, said Tom 
Lux, who was handing out summaries. He predicted it would pass. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is great! All of it!'' declared Robert MacDuff, 53, a  
Boeing worker from Lakewood. 
</P>
<P>
	Weekend work was ``a strike issue,'' he said. ``If they had gone  
to that, this company would have been shut down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal keeps the traditional work week, meaning workers  
would continue to be paid overtime for working on weekends; it has 
no increase in worker fees for medical benefits; and it includes a 
25 percent increase in pension benefits, a 10 percent signing bonus 
and annual wage increases of 4 percent, 4 percent and 3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	It also allows review by union member of proposals to contract  
work to outside companies. The company, however, retains the right 
to decide when to contract out work. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers will decide if they agree with Johnson on Wednesday  
-- the day their current contract expires. A majority vote in favor 
would ratify the contract. A two-thirds majority would be required 
in a separate vote to authorize a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Many union members, like Cliff Standfill, a 20-year Boeing  
employee in Renton, Wash., said job security was the most important 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a money issue,'' Standfill said. ``It never has  
been.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said the company promised that no employees would be  
laid off because of contracting out work. The company's offer also 
would provide 180 days' notice when work is to be contracted out 
and establish a joint committee to review such proposals, but the 
company would still make the final decision, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal summary said the no-layoff promise does not apply  
to offsets, a practice of assigning jobs to workers chosen by 
airplane customers, such as China. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson praised Boeing Chairman Phil Condit as a ``visionary''  
who understands union members. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a whole bunch we've got to do,'' Condit said  
Saturday as he shook hands with Johnson at a news conference. ``If 
we work together, we can make this place tremendously competitive, 
and that's what we're after.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the negotiations, Condit said cost was the bottom line  
for Boeing, the world's largest aerospace company, and he 
emphasized the company's competition from European rival Airbus 
Industrie. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing is undertaking a massive job cut program to reduce its  
work force from a high of 238,000 in June 1998 to between 185,000 
and 195,000 by the end of next year. The Seattle-based company 
currently employs about 206,000 worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've done our best, and I think we've delivered an agreement  
that our employees ... will at the end of the day find very, very 
attractive,'' Boeing lead negotiator Jerry Calhoun said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Machinists struck Boeing in two of their last three  
negotiations, including a 69-day strike in 1995. Boeing workers in 
Seattle, Portland, Ore., and Wichita, Kan., had voted informally in 
July to support another strike if negotiations failed. 
</P>
<P>
	The current contract covers 31,000 workers in Washington state,  
1,400 in Portland and 11,600 in Wichita. The average machinist at 
Boeing earns $40,000 a year, not counting benefits or overtime. 







  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
