<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 13:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vermont Town Had 1 Crime Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRANBY, Vt. (AP) -- Town Clerk Nellie Noble didn't know. Neither  
did Jeff Brown, who took a break from building Granby's first store 
to ponder the question. Betty Brown, his cousin who lives just down 
the road, shut off her lawnmower to think. She didn't know, either. 
</P>
<P>
	So just what was Granby's only crime of 1998?  
</P>
<P>
	State police, court record-keepers, the local game warden, the  
Essex County sheriff's dispatcher: None of them had any idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet there it is. Of 73,370 crimes reported in the state last  
year, Granby tallied one: a fraud, recorded without elaboration in 
Vermont's 1998 crime report. 
</P>
<P>
	``It probably isn't anybody from Granby,'' Noble said. ``Who  
knows?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown thought he did. Someone stole his father's pickup truck,  
but Brown saw the perpetrator maneuver across the lawn and called 
the sheriff, who caught him on the road out of town. 
</P>
<P>
	But the thief was from nearby Lancaster, N.H.  
</P>
<P>
	And it wasn't last year.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the only crime I know of here,'' Brown said. And he  
means in the 38 years, his entire life, he's lived in the northeast 
Vermont town. 
</P>
<P>
	Granby -- population roughly 90 -- is the essence of small town,  
where almost everyone is related and even those who aren't know 
each other like cousins. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are used to going into other people's homes and taking  
things out of the cupboard,'' says Betty Brown, who married into 
one of the community's longtime families 25 years ago. ``Then we'll 
call them up later and tell them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Isolation keeps Granby tight-knit. It takes a 20-minute drive  
over potholed roads to reach a state highway. 
</P>
<P>
	Granby also boasts one of the state's last one-room elementary  
schools. It has one teacher and nine students. For the annual class 
trip, the whole town is invited, and most people go. The town 
supports school clubs and the church, and although there isn't much 
speeding, donations from residents bought a used radar gun for 
Sheriff Amos Colby. 
</P>
<P>
	Crime is simply not something Granby residents think about.  
</P>
<P>
	``We did have a camp in Granby where there was a party going on.  
We had to resolve that and take some people back to (jail in) St. 
Johnsbury,'' Colby said. 
</P>
<P>
	When?  
</P>
<P>
	``Eight or nine years ago.''  
</P>
<P>
	It took Colby most of a day to track down the details of last  
year's crime. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 9, 1998, a man wrote Fred Hodgdon a $300 check for six  
piglets. The check bounced, and the man couldn't be found. The case 
remains open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think nothing about that,'' Hodgdon said.  
</P>
<P>
	He could well be Granby's lone crime victim for 1999 as well,  
but it won't appear in the state crime report. Hodgdon didn't 
report it. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, a woman bought four piglets from him and paid  
cash. He didn't count the money until later when he discovered he'd 
been shorted by half. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident didn't shake his faith in people or his hometown.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't trade it for any other place,'' he says. ``If they  
wanted something, I'd give it to them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 19:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants Center Williams Sprains Knee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- New York Giants center Brian  
Williams, who is attempting a comeback after missing two seasons 
with an eye injury, sprained his left knee in the first half of 
Saturday night's exhibition against the New York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams was injured on the Giants' second possession but it was  
not clear on what play. Derek Engler took over at center. 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants also lost defensive tackle Robert Harris with a  
sprained left ankle on the opening series of the game. 
  	   	
</P>
