<DOCNO> APW19990828.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 14:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gymnastics Champ To Play Dual Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- John Roethlisberger had just completed  
a remarkable comeback to the U.S. gymnastics team. Yet he realized 
performing on the floor will be only one of the roles he'll have to 
play on the national squad. 
</P>
<P>
	Roethlisberger, 29, a four-time national champion in the early  
1990s, placed second in the all-around competition Friday night to 
make the national team less than a year after reconstructive 
surgery on his right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to performing, he expects to act as mentor and  
emotional guide for Jason Gatson, one of the nation's top male 
gymnasts who tore a ligament in his right knee Friday night while 
leading the all-around competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson, 18, whose knee buckled as he dismounted from the  
horizontal bar, is expected to have surgery in the next few weeks. 
He flew back to the U.S. Olympic Training Center in Colorado 
Springs, Colo., on Saturday for further examination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought about what my role would be in these four years  
after 1996. Maybe that's one of the things I need to do is to help 
Jason,'' Roethlisberger said. ``I know how he's feeling right now. 
There's not much of a worse feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The women were set to compete in individual events Saturday on  
the closing night of the U.S. Gymnastics Championships. Kristen 
Maloney won the women's all-around title Thursday, edging Vanessa 
Atler for the second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	Blaine Wilson captured an unprecedented fourth straight men's  
national all-around title with a nearly flawless performance in 
Friday's finals after Gatson hurt himself on the night's opening 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson's overall score of 115.300 points made him the first man  
to win four national titles since Roethlisberger won in 1990, '92, 
'93 and '95. But he was not interested in celebrating -- instead, he 
was thinking of Gatson, his training partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll probably spend most of my time seeing how he's doing,''  
Wilson said. ``Jason obviously is a big link in our team. He will 
be missed, but he will be back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roethlisberger finished second with a score of 111.800. Brett  
McClure was third with 111.500. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 14 men and 14 women in the all-around competition  
qualify for the World Championships team trials, to be held Sept. 
15-18 in Kansas City. That event will help choose the American 
squad for the World Gymnastics Championships Oct. 8-16 in Tianjin, 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson, who finished second in 1996 and '98 and was third in the  
national championships in 1997, held a slim lead over Wilson at the 
start of the all-around finals Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	But his right knee buckled as he flew off the high bar, and he  
fell to the side of the mat. After getting iced on the competition 
floor, he was helped to the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	Gatson was second in the national all-around competition in 1996  
and '98, losing both times to Wilson. He was third in 1997 behind 
Wilson and Roethlisberger. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury threatens to keep one of the United States' most  
promising male gymnasts out of the Sydney Olympics, though Gatson 
predicted he will return from the injury in time for the 2000 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as I landed, something popped and I just fell to the  
ground, it hurt so bad. I knew something happened, because it was a 
loud pop. My knee just went out on me,'' Gatson said. ``This is 
going to make me stronger. I am going to get it fixed and I am 
going to come back and be on the Olympic team in Sydney.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roethlisberger, who competed with a leg brace at the  
championships and wore three huge ice packs on his legs during a 
post-competition news conference, said he's also confident Gatson 
will be fully healed before the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll be back, no problem, I guarantee,'' Roethlisberger said.  
``It's going to be a tough year for him. But for sure he's going to 
be back up here next year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 00:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson: Not Getting Respect Earned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- In a way, Michael Johnson is similar to  
Babe Ruth, and he doesn't get nearly as much credit for his 
accomplishments. 
</P>
<P>
	``Twice, Michael predicted what he was going to do,'' coach  
Clyde Hart said Friday, ``just like Babe Ruth did when he said he 
was going to hit a home run for the little boy in the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``For Atlanta (at the 1996 Olympics), he said he was going to  
double (in the 200 and 400 meters) and do something special,'' Hart 
added, referring to Johnson's astonishing world record of 19.32 
seconds for the 200. ``This year, he said he wanted to win the 
world championship and set a world record -- and he did it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the sign of a great athlete.''  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's athletic greatness is unquestionable. He has won three  
Olympic gold medals, a record-tying eight gold medals at the World 
Championships and is only the second man to hold world records in 
the 200 and 400 simultaneously, joining Tommie Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately for track and field's most outstanding athlete of  
the decade, he has been unduly criticized often. Johnson and Hart 
feel the criticism is unjustified. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson doesn't even think his latest feat, breaking Butch  
Reynolds' 11-year-old record of 43.29 in the 400 with a remarkable 
43.18 Thursday night at the World Championships, will silence 
critics. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are going to say whatever they want,'' he said. ``I  
need to try not to let it get to me. This year, I let it get to me 
a little more, but I was able to regroup and get back to what I do 
best and that's keeping my mouth shut and running on the track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What rankled Johnson and Hart most were insinuations during the  
USA Championships at Eugene, Ore., in June that the sprint great 
was ducking 100-meter world record-holder Maurice Greene. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were supposed to meet in a much-hyped 200 showdown at  
the championships, but Johnson withdrew at the last minute because 
of a chronic hip alignment problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime Michael doesn't run against Maurice, people say he's  
ducking Maurice,'' Hart said. ``When Maurice doesn't run against 
Michael, people don't write that Maurice is ducking Michael.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said his next race would be a 200 at Brussels, Belgium,  
on Sept. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Maurice wants to come there and run, fine,'' Johnson said.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson will complete his season with another 200 at Rieti,  
Italy, on Sept. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, he will rest before beginning preparations for another  
200-400 double at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	The usually unflappable Johnson almost didn't get to the World  
Championships. He became so frustrated after being forced to stop 
in mid-race during a 200 at Stockholm on July 30 that he was ready 
to end his season then. 
</P>
<P>
	``That brought him to the low edge,'' Hart said. ``He was  
depressed, he was down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart convinced him to continue, telling him he could whip him  
into shape by the championships and that he could break the 400 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, Johnson wanted to run at the lucrative Golden League meet  
at Zurich, Switzerland, on Aug. 11. Hart, who has coached Johnson 
for 14 years, didn't think that was the smartest move, and told 
Johnson to keep training. 
</P>
<P>
	He gave him a rigorous schedule of 12 workouts in 13 days, doing  
a series of 350-meter runs with little rest in between. Those tough 
workouts continued after Johnson arrived in Seville. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Johnson ran his first-round heat last Sunday, he was  
ready mentally and physically. His attitude toward running changed 
completely, going from sour to sweet, and his health was fine. 
</P>
<P>
	As each round of the 400 unfolded, it was evident he was primed  
for a memorable performance. He gave it Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	People noticed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Michael looked super,'' said Mel Rosen, the U.S. men's Olympic  
coach in 1992. ``He looks like he can do anything he wants. 
</P>
<P>
	``This record will last 20 years. The 200 record will last 50  
years. The 200 is a better record than the 400.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George Williams, the U.S. men's coach at the World  
Championships, was impressed with Johnson's performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been coaching more than 28 years, and that's one of the  
best races I've ever seen,'' he said. ``Not only in the 
quarter-mile, but any race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The scintillating victory triggered calls for a match race  
between Johnson and Greene, the world's two fastest sprinters, 
similar to the highly hyped duel between Johnson and Donovan Bailey 
in 1997. During that race, Johnson tore his right quadriceps muscle 
and didn't finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson and Hart scotched the latest suggestion.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's anything for me to gain from it,''  
Johnson said. ``Leave those for the Olympic trials and Olympic 
Games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calling the Bailey race ``infamous,'' Hart said Johnson still  
has repercussions from the quad injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``He sometimes feels it when he's running slow,'' Hart said.  
``It's taken him two years to get his conditioning back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Johnson's conditioning holds up into next year's Olympics,  
he'll probably go for the 400 record in a quest for an 
unprecedented double-double in the sprints. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps two world records in his two Olympic specialties and his  
second straight sweep would finally give him the recognition he 
deserves. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 14:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gymnastics Champ To Play Dual Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- John Roethlisberger had just completed  
