<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lasorda Manages One More Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- So you a have a minor league  
baseball team, your manager is unavailable and you need to find a 
replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	How about a Hall of Famer?  
</P>
<P>
	Former Los Angeles Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda returned to the  
dugout Friday to lead the Class A Vero Beach Dodgers to a 1-0 win 
in a Florida State League game against the St. Lucie Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	Vero Beach manager Alvaro Espinoza, whose wife recently had a  
baby, was unavailable. 
</P>
<P>
	Lasorda, the Dodgers' senior vice president, was in town to  
evaluate players and was asked to step in for one game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice,'' Lasorda said. ``But I'm just down here. My  
purpose in coming here is to look at the players, evaluate them, 
motivate them, inspire them. They asked me to do this, so I thought 
I'd do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Lasorda's first time managing since he retired three  
years ago because of heart problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Lasorda was elected to the baseball Hall of Fame in 1997 by the  
Veterans Committee in his first year of eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``I miss managing, I really do,'' Lasorda said. ``But when I had  
my heart problem, I just felt that I'd had enough of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's game was Lasorda's first minor league management stint  
in 27 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the first time I've ever managed a team since I retired,  
so it better be a winning one,'' he said before the game. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
