<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rookie Sets Pace in IRL Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOUNTAIN, Colo. (AP) -- With a logjam at the top of the point  
standings and three races remaining, the chase for the Indy Racing 
League's $1 million bonus is anybody's game. 
</P>
<P>
	Just ask those in the lead.  
</P>
<P>
	On the eve of the Colorado Indy 200, Scott Goodyear leads the  
standings with 193 points, Greg Ray has 191 and Kenny Brack 179. 
But six other drivers are within a single victory -- worth 50 points 
-- of taking over the lead, and four others are realistically within 
striking distance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The three of us might wind up in the infield on Sunday,''  
Goodyear noted, ``and it might be three different people you're 
looking at at Texas (the final race on Oct. 17). You've got guys 
who are running strong and haven't won yet, hard chargers like Sam 
Schmidt and Jeff Ward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Ray, who triumphed in the Radisson 200 here on June 27,  
``The way the point structure is, it changes so drastically, so 
quickly. One guy can have a bad weekend and he can go from second 
to eighth. Or you can go from sixth to first real quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Scott Harrington is far off the pace, but he too is  
capable of making some noise. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington had the fastest times in Friday's two practice  
sessions in preparation for today's qualifying and Sunday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington turned a lap of 175.234 mph in the morning session on  
Pikes Peak International Raceway's one-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt was next at 173.972 mph, and Ward was timed in 173.871.  
</P>
<P>
	In the afternoon, Harrington went 174.258 mph, bettering Robby  
McGehee, at 172.538, and Ward, at 172.166. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodyear, Ray and Brack all posted modest practice speeds on  
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months ago on this track, Harrington was poised for a  
top-three finish -- and possibly a win -- when he brushed the wall 
with 17 laps to go. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were reeling in Sam (Schmidt, the race's runnerup) and  
Greg,'' Harrington recalled. ``I feel like we should have won that 
one. I definitely feel we let that one get away from us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He challenged for the lead despite driving with a broken right  
leg, torn ligaments in his left knee and three cracked ribs as a 
result of a crash two weeks earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Harrington still wore a brace on his left knee, but  
he said he was significantly improved. 
</P>
<P>
	``Physically, I'm way better,'' he said. ``Probably the biggest  
thing I'm dealing with now is the physical conditioning. I had a 
pretty regular routine of working out. Then I had injuries to both 
legs, and the ribs prevented me from doing much upper-body work. 
The conditioning definitely has suffered, but in the last four 
weeks I've been able to do a lot more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His car, meanwhile, remains in superb condition.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're using pretty much the same setup we had in June,'' he  
said. ``Very minor changes. This afternoon, we got close to where 
we were this morning. We figured we knew what we needed to know so 
we decided to park it and skip the last part of the session. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've just got a great race car this weekend. This is  
definitely the fastest car we've had all year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington, 35, of Indianapolis admitted that his team remains  
basically a shoestring operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've run one engine since Charlotte (on May 1),'' he said.  
``We rebuild it every weekend. It's kind of hard for us to practice 
pit stops because we only have two guys who work for us. The rest 
of the guys are volunteers and weekend help. It's hard for me to 
sit in the car and plug the air jack in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jimmy Kite lost an engine during the morning session and did not  
practice in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyce Carlson caused heavy damage to the rear of his car when he  
hit the wall in Turn 4. Carlson wasn't hurt, and he turned several 
laps in his backup car in the afternoon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
