<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Brewers Interview Stewart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The Milwaukee Brewers have interviewed Toronto  
assistant general manager Dave Stewart as part of a search to 
replace former general manager Sal Bando, according to the 
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper, citing unidentified sources, also said that Wendy  
Selig-Prieb, the Brewers' president and chief executive officer, 
will interview former Cleveland Indians assistant general manager 
Dan O'Dowd on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig-Prieb has refused to comment on the search process for a  
new GM, the Journal Sentinel reported in Sunday's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Phil Garner was fired and Bando was reassigned Aug. 12,  
as the Brewers appeared headed to their seventh straight losing 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who was interviewed by Selig-Prieb on Thursday, said he  
was the first candidate interviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I answered questions, told her what I thought of their club,  
their minor league system and scouting,'' Stewart said. ``There is 
a lot to build on there as they move into their new park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers currently are building a new stadium, called Miller  
Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, 42, was a four-time 20-game winner during a 15-year  
major league career with five clubs. He played on three World 
Series championship teams. 
</P>
<P>
	After finishing his playing career with Oakland in 1995, he  
worked for a year as the A's assistant general manager before 
moving to San Diego. After one year as an assistant to general 
manager Kevin Towers, he moved into the dugout as the pitching 
coach and helped guide the Padres to the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	He then moved to Toronto.  
</P>
<P>
	O'Dowd, 41, has spent 17 seasons in professional baseball, most  
recently in Cleveland, where he helped build the Indians farm 
system into one of the strongest in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball sources said last week that the Brewers had compiled a  
list of 12 potential candidates, including Stewart, O'Dowd, former 
Dodgers general manager Fred Claire, New York Mets assistant GM 
Omar Minaya, Chicago White Sox director of baseball operations Dan 
Evans; and Cincinnati Reds assistant GM Darrell ``Doc'' Rodgers, 
the Journal Sentinel reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Yankees GM Bob Watson and Cleveland scout Ted Simmons  
also are believed to be on the list, the Journal Sentinel reported. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
