<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> West Bank Pullback in Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators tried  
Saturday to resolve the final barriers to implementing a 
U.S.-brokered peace accord ahead of a visit to the region by U.S. 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. 
</P>
<P>
	Differences over Israel's promised release of Palestinian  
prisoners has been holding up a long-delayed deal to turn over more 
of the West Bank to Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority. 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, the two sides apparently had ironed out most of the  
details to clear the way for Israel's withdrawal from 11 percent of 
the West Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting top Palestinian negotiators at her Washington home  
on Friday, Albright told reporters, ``I think we are looking 
forward to the conclusion of this aspect of the peace process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat met with  
his Israeli counterpart, Gilead Sher, at a Jerusalem hotel. The 
talks lasted for three hours, but neither side provided details on 
their contents. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiators were slated to meet again Sunday, Israel radio  
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat met with his Israeli  
counterpart, Gilead Sher, at a Jerusalem hotel on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright is expected to participate Thursday in a signing  
ceremony in Alexandria, Egypt, if the agreement is worked out in 
time. The peace deal would be the first to be signed under the rule 
of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who came to power in July. 
</P>
<P>
	During the meeting with the Palestinian negotiators, Albright  
promised to try to help find a solution for the issue of prisoners, 
said Hasan Abdel Rahman, the PLO representative in Washington who 
participated in the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians are demanding the release of detainees jailed  
for involvement in anti-Israel activities. Israel insists it will 
not free prisoners with ``blood on their hands'' -- meaning 
prisoners connected to attacks that injured or killed Israelis. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat's cabinet, meeting Friday, stressed the importance of the  
prisoner issue in a statement, saying the matter is ``one of the 
most important and sensitive issues for the Palestinian people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	International cooperation minister Nabil Shaath was optimistic  
about the chances an understanding could be reached soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no doubt that we are closer. The differences have  
been narrowed and some topics have been concluded,'' Shaath said. 
</P>
<P>
	The sides are trying to iron out differences on just how to  
implement the U.S.-brokered Wye accord, signed in October by former 
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who then froze 
implementation of the agreement in December. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the emerging deal, Israel will withdraw from 11  
percent of the West Bank by the end of January and establish ``safe 
passage'' routes for Palestinians to travel between the Gaza Strip 
and West Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians will also be allowed through the agreement to  
open a port in the Gaza Strip. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
