<DOCNO> APW19990828.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 05:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 27, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Threatens Bahamas, U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Whipping up gale-force winds that doubled  
over coconut palms and storm surges that crashed onto roadways, 
Hurricane Dennis closed in on the northern Bahamas and threatened 
to strike Florida. Forecasters said Dennis could strengthen and hit 
the United States as a major storm today, clawing up the Florida 
coast and heading into North Carolina by Monday. From hundreds of 
miles away, Dennis kicked up 8-foot-high waves off Florida and 
North Carolina, delighting surfers but prompting officials to put 
state troopers and the National Guard on alert. Hurricane watches 
and tropical storm warnings were issued along hundreds of miles of 
the eastern seaboard. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesian Landslide Kills Dozens  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Rain triggered a landslide at a  
government-run gold mine in Indonesia's West Java province, killing 
at least 30 miners, news reports said today. The Berita Buana 
newspaper reported that about 10 other miners were missing and 
believed trapped under the earth and rocks. The landslide occurred 
on Wednesday. It was the second fatal landslide at the Pongkor mine 
near Bogor, 50 miles southeast of the capital of Jakarta, this 
year. 

</P>
<P>
	Several Killed in Yemen Blasts  
</P>
<P>
	SAN`A, Yemen (AP) -- Authorities refuse to speculate if bomb  
blasts, which killed several people in three Yemen cities, were 
related. In the Yemeni capital of San`a today, a car bomb killed 
several people, injured many others, and damaged a number of 
embassies and diplomatic homes. No diplomatic personnel were 
injured in the 2 a.m. explosion outside a supermarket in the Hadda 
area, which came hours after two bombs went off in southern Yemen. 
Officials could not give an exact number of casualties in the 
latest explosion. In the southern port city of Aden, a bomb 
exploded near the National Bank building, slightly damaging the 
walls surrounding the building. And in Zinjibar, a bomb went off in 
front of the prosecutors's office. Authorities refused to speculate 
if the three blasts were related. 

</P>
<P>
	Explosion Hits Downtown Pristina  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A strong explosion rocked downtown  
Pristina today, damaging a communist-era monument to ethnic harmony 
and reflecting anew the hatreds bedeviling international efforts to 
establish normality in postwar Kosovo. Nobody was hurt in the 
predawn explosion, said members of the NATO-led peacekeeping force, 
but the power of the blast rattled windows in a section of the 
Kosovo capital. The three-pronged concrete Brotherhood and Unity 
monument was erected during the rule of Josip Broz Tito, founder of 
communist Yugoslavia and a proponent of multiethnic coexistence. 
Tito died in 1980, and the breakup of Yugoslavia along ethnic lines 
turned bloody a decade later, with the Serb-Albanian conflict in 
Kosovo just the latest conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Punishing Shoddy Builders  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Responding to widespread anger at  
shoddily constructed buildings that collapsed during last week's 
earthquake, the Turkish parliament passed a bill today that 
attempts to relieve overcrowded jails by giving amnesty to 
thousands of prisoners -- excluding builders. The bill frees 
juveniles and some prisoners who received sentences of up to 12 
years and would have included builders convicted of negligence. 
Their exclusion was mainly a symbolic gesture, since few have been 
prosecuted in the past for haphazard building practices. Builders 
drew nationwide ire after the Aug. 17 quake flattened thousands of 
poorly constructed buildings, killing 13,479 people and injuring 
tens of thousands. Several thousand bodies are believed to be still 
buried under the rubble. 

</P>
<P>
	Waco Filmmaker Finds Satisfaction  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- For years, filmmaker Michael McNulty accused the  
government of lying about its actions during the seven-week 
confrontation with Branch Davidians that ended in fiery tragedy in 
1993. Finally this week, after years of denials, the government 
admitted it did use pyrotechnic devices the day the Davidian's 
Mount Caramel compound burned down, killing David Koresh and about 
80 followers. But while McNulty said he is gratified the truth is 
finally coming out -- he believes there is more that is yet to be 
revealed. ``Getting answers is satisfying, but it will be much more 
satisfying when the people who are responsible are in prison,'' he 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Owners Warn Umps on Strike  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Baseball owners have told umpires they will be  
fired if they strike next week. AL president Gene Budig and NL 
president Len Coleman sent the warning in an Aug. 25 memo that many 
umpires received before they worked last night's games. Some of the 
umpires backing union head Richie Phillips have talked about 
striking over baseball's refusal to allow 22 umpires to withdraw 
their resignations, which are effective Thursday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 10:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mississippi Gov. Hopeful Risked All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- For a longshot chance to become  
Mississippi's governor, Dan Gibson gave up most of his worldly 
possessions -- a $208,000 antebellum home, two Cadillacs and antique 
furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	It was God's will that he do so, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, trounced in his party's primary, he's without a job and  
living in a one-bedroom apartment with his wife, Tonya, and 
5-year-old son, Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I would have loved to have won, but looking back on  
it, I really wasn't prepared for it,'' Gibson said with an 
interminably upbeat, Southern drawl. ``I need more maturity. Not 
only in government and politics, but more maturity as a 
Christian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last spring, the former real estate agent gave up the post of  
mayor of Crystal Springs, to which he was elected in 1996, and sold 
his possessions to finance his longshot bid to win the Republican 
nomination for the state's highest office. 
</P>
<P>
	He came in fourth in a six-candidate field in the Aug. 3  
primary. Former U.S. Rep. Mike Parker won the nomination to face 
Democratic Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove in November. 
</P>
<P>
	But no one will hear the 34-year-old Gibson complaining about  
the downturn in his life. 
</P>
<P>
	``God is providing. We have not had to beg for bread and I don't  
think we are going to,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He calls his new Jackson apartment ``cozy.'' He acknowledges  
that it is old and says that as soon as he and his wife moved in 
they started painting the walls. 
</P>
<P>
	Until he bought a used car this past week, he had been driving a  
pickup borrowed from a fellow member of his church. 
</P>
<P>
	Just months ago, the family lived in a 4,300-square-foot house  
with five bedrooms and 2 1/2 baths. Now, all three share a bedroom, 
with a separate bed for Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	Tonya Gibson, 27, said making the transition from the large  
house to the apartment has been ``physically hard and mentally 
hard,'' but said selling the house was for the best. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never utilized the house that we had so it really didn't  
make sense (to keep it),'' she said. ``At one point, I had wished 
that we had our cars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since his election loss, Gibson has received one offer. He said  
he's interested in returning to real estate, or possibly starting a 
nonprofit organization focusing on family issues. He also won't 
rule out staying in politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson says he has no regrets about trying to win over voters  
with a platform promising to bring God back to politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``God's way is higher than our ways,'' he said. ``Sometimes we  
don't see the full picture until we go through something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others believe Gibson sacrificed too much.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's an incredible commitment he made,'' said former  
gubernatorial candidate Pete Johnson. ``I've known governors as far 
back as J.P. Coleman in the 50s, and I have never heard of any 
candidate selling his house to put money in the campaign. That's a 
commitment that's above and beyond the call of duty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, a Clarksdale lawyer who lost the Republican nomination  
to Gov. Kirk Fordice in 1991, said Gibson should be admired for his 
sacrifice. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the eyes of many it was something quite foolish, but I've  
got to respect that,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson said he is not broke, and has always had a place to lay  
his head since selling his house, with the family even invited to 
live with supporters after the election. 
</P>
<P>
	``God has just really blessed us through this whole thing,'' he  
said with a smile. ``The most important thing is that we have 
learned so much about what is important in life. Family, even being 
in a one-bedroom apartment, is so much more important than keeping 
up with the Joneses.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 00:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
