<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Slams Clinton on Veto Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arizona Gov. Jane Hull accused President  
Clinton today of playing politics with Americans' money by 
threatening to veto the $792 billion in tax cuts passed by 
Republicans last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining a list of Republican governors and members of Congress  
who have used the GOP's weekly radio address this summer to tout 
the tax cuts, Hull asked rhetorically why Clinton would veto the 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``He either has a deep-seated desire to increase government  
spending, or he just does not want to give the money back to the 
people who earned it in the first place,'' she said. ``President 
Clinton is playing politics with your money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House says the Republican tax-cut plan, if enacted,  
would squeeze future budgets to the point where it would force 
automatic cuts in Medicare and other basic federal services. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Clinton said the proposed 10-year tax cut  
would create ``an impossible budgeting problem'' requiring cuts of 
nearly 50 percent in programs ranging from education to air traffic 
control to the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Over a decade, the bill would reduce all income tax rates by one  
percentage point, cut capital gains taxes, improve retirement 
savings, ease the ``marriage penalty'' paid by many two-income 
couples, gradually eliminate the alternative minimum tax, provide 
new breaks for education and health care and benefit large and 
small businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
