<DOCNO> APW19990828.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 13:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Forgoes Waldorf Astoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A swanky, $30,000-a-month suite above the  
Waldorf Astoria Hotel, traditionally reserved for the U.S. 
ambassador to the United Nations, has been occupied by a junior 
staffer since Ambassador Richard C. Holbrooke decided to pass it 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	The new ambassador will continue to live in his private home in  
Manhattan rather than the Waldorf suite -- one of the most 
sought-after U.S. diplomatic residences, The Washington Post 
reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Holbrooke's 27-year-old assistant, R.P. Eddy, will  
enjoy the luxury digs until he finds his own apartment. The young 
man is being allowed to stay there to save the government the money 
for a separate hotel room, the Post reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The official ambassador's residence has mostly been vacant since  
last September, when Bill Richardson left to become President 
Clinton's energy secretary. Holbrooke reportedly plans to use it to 
entertain foreign dignitaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke was sworn in as ambassador this week after a 14-month  
delay in his confirmation by the Senate, a delay caused by 
Republican-erected hurdles and an ethics investigation that has 
since been resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke was on an official visit to the Balkans on Saturday,  
and neither he nor his staff were available for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Waldorf suite is in the Art Deco ``Towers'' section of the  
hotel, with a separate entrance on 51st Street between Park and 
Lexington avenues. It has been used as the official U.S. 
ambassador's residence since 1949. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
