<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opponent's Title Entices Mullings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- David Reid is more concerned with Keith  
Mullings than he is with his droopy left eyelid. 
</P>
<P>
	``Keith Mullings is a tough guy, but that's what we're here  
for,'' Reid said. ``There's only going to be one winner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid defends his WBA 154-pound title tonight against Mullings,  
who held the WBC version of the title before losing it earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll do it once again with the droopy left eyelid that proves  
so enticing to his opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``People question my eye, but it's not a big deal,'' Reid said.  
``I know I'm not worried about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid has undergone three different operations to repair the  
eyelid, which tends to come down in fights and limits his vision 
out of the left eye. 
</P>
<P>
	But the problem hasn't damaged the career of the 1996 Olympic  
gold medalist, who is undefeated in 13 fights and won the WBA title 
March 6 with a decision over Laurent Boudouani. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing wrong with the eyeball, it's the eyelid that  
comes down,'' Reid's trainer, Al Mitchell, said. ``Sometimes it 
comes down in a fight and sometimes it doesn't. But he can see, and 
that's the main thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the eye has proven to be an attractive target for Reid's  
opponents, and Mullings is no exception. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely something to go after,'' Mullings said. ``But  
I may just go after the other eye and close that one, too. Then 
he'll be totally blind in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid will make the second defense of his title -- and the second  
in just six weeks -- in the scheduled 12-round fight on a card at 
the Hard Rock hotel-casino that will be televised on HBO beginning 
at 11 p.m. EDT. Both fighters weighed in Friday at the class limit 
of 154 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last fight, Reid was knocked down by Kevin Kelly and  
taken the distance for the third straight time, but still ended up 
with a unanimous decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid, who stopped seven of his first 10 opponents, hasn't  
knocked anyone down since, while hitting the canvas three times 
himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not really worried about it because I'm getting the  
wins,'' the 25-year-old from Philadelphia said. ``Whenever a guy 
looks like he's a superior fighter and he gets taken to the 
distance, people question him. But I'm at the top of my game and 
I'm very confident in myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid is a 4-1 favorite against Mullings, who held the WBC  
version of the 154-pound title after stopping Terry Norris in the 
ninth round Nov. 6, 1997, in a shocking upset. 
</P>
<P>
	Mullings (16-5-1, 11 knockouts) didn't enjoy his championship  
reign long, though, losing the title after only one defense in a 
disputed 12-round split decision to Francisco Castillejo in Spain 
on Jan. 29. It was the fourth split decision loss of Mullings' 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Beating Reid would finally give me the recognition I  
deserve,'' said Mullings, a 31-year-old from Brooklyn, N.Y., who 
began his pro career at the age of 25 following a stint in the Army 
that saw him serve in Desert Storm. ``If I beat the gold medal 
winner, I'll be the one people are talking about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the card is undefeated heavyweight Monte Barrett of New  
York, who will put his 21-0 record against Lance Whitaker, a 
6-foot-8 puncher who lost for the first time in 19 pro fights when 
he dropped a 10-round decision to Lou Savarese on March 6. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
