<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Doctor Using Turkey Connections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- The doctor has treated not one patient  
since arriving in his ravaged homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	That was never his plan. Dr. Sait Tarhan of Minnesota's Mayo  
Clinic came to save lives by pulling strings. His friends here are 
government officials, powerful journalists, the rich and the 
well-connected. 
</P>
<P>
	In Turkey, ``I wouldn't go anywhere without him,'' said an aid  
worker with Connecticut-based AmeriCares, which brought Tarhan and 
41 tons of supplies last week on a DC-8 cargo jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Tarhan's group arrived five days after a 7.4-magnitude  
earthquake crippled Turkey on Aug. 17, killing more than 12,000 
people and injuring some 30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Even under normal circumstances, the bloated Turkish bureaucracy  
is moribund. Now, it barely staggers along and Tarhan's connections 
are invaluable. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tarhan, a Turk who emigrated to America in 1958, was on the  
job before he landed here. When the quake set a giant refinery 
burning out of control, he called friends at the Ankara government 
crisis center and gave them the name of a Texas company that helped 
extinguish Kuwait's raging oil field fires during the Gulf War. 
</P>
<P>
	The firefighters came. But Tarhan does not take credit. ``I  
doubt it was because of me,'' he said, eating breakfast at his 
hotel before leaving to check distribution efforts at the giant 
warehouse holding AmeriCares relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Tarhan refuses to say exactly whom he knows in high places.  
</P>
<P>
	But he does say how he knows them.  
</P>
<P>
	For 35 years, he was an anesthesiologist at one of the  
prestigious Mayo clinics, which treat patients from all over the 
world. He tried to retire in 1997, but hospital administrators 
talked him into staying. Now he arranges all travel and medical 
needs for patients arriving from Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	In both jobs, he helped some of the country's highest-ranking  
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is how I move things around here,'' he said. ``I have  
established really close friendships. You help people out in their 
most desperate moments, and they never forget you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So ``when I call them up and say `I need your help. How can we  
make something happen?' They will give their help without 
hesitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is nervous about being interviewed. ``What are you going to  
write, eh?'' he asks several times. ``Please be careful not to make 
it look like I am exploiting my friendships with these people. 
Please be kind. Because we may need them again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second time he has accompanied AmeriCares to Turkey  
after an earthquake. The first was in 1992, when 485 were killed by 
a 6.5-magnitude quake in the central city of Ercinzan. 
</P>
<P>
	He speaks fluent Turkish and is forever on his cell phone,  
arranging meetings and ways to distribute medicine, blankets and 
tents. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, accompanied by two aid workers and four journalists,  
he finagled his way into the country's largest navy installation, 
which has been sealed since the quake. 
</P>
<P>
	The naval base is in Golcuk, one of Turkey's hardest-hit cities.  
More than 2,000 people died. At least 500 were Navy personnel, many 
of them top-ranking officers. The secretive military tried to play 
down its loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I called a very powerful (newspaper) columnist. He called up  
and told the navy that some people were coming from the Mayo Clinic 
and that was that,'' said Tarhan. ``In every country, it's not what 
you know, it's who you know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the shattered base, where military headquarters operated  
under tents in pouring rain, Tarhan huddled with an admiral, 
speaking rapid-fire Turkish. Eventually the conversation turned to 
English, with several officers joining in. They needed temporary 
shelter, they told Tarhan, while an aid worker scribbled notes. 
</P>
<P>
	They also needed surgical kits and portable toilets, sleeping  
bags and tents. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Tarhan was asked what the admiral had said to him in  
Turkish. ``I think all military people are very careful, very 
secretive,'' he said. Then he smiled and winked. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days later, he stood outside a housing project near Izmit,  
another heavily damaged area. With him were the AmeriCares workers 
and two representatives of tobacco giant Philip Morris, which has 
offered to help erect a 200-tent city and provide food to its 
inhabitants until more permanent housing can be built. 
</P>
<P>
	The cigarette maker ``has a big presence in this country because  
the Turkish people just smoke way the hell too much.'' Tarhan 
chuckled. ``So let's just say, maybe this gives them a chance to 
repay the favor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tarhan, now 67, was just out of the army when he came to America  
41 years ago to complete his medical residency. After four years of 
working in Kentucky and Ohio hospitals, he sent an application to 
the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., thinking he was not good 
enough to get in. 
</P>
<P>
	But he was accepted. He chose to specialize in anesthesiology  
because ``I thought it was the easiest. I would be in the operating 
room all morning and playing golf in the afternoon,'' he joked. 
</P>
<P>
	His sense of humor is self-deprecating and mischievous. It also  
covers a sensitive heart. 
</P>
<P>
	He has always come home to Turkey, to visit family and to  
vacation with his American wife and two sons. 
</P>
<P>
	Tarhan was 4 when his Turkish family escaped the Russians in  
Crimea and fled to this country. 
</P>
<P>
	He loves Turkey and its people, and he is haunted by the  
devastation he sees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes an imprint on your subconscious,'' he said. ``And it  
comes back at the most unexpected times, like a movie that runs in 
your head. And it is the same one all the time -- the suffering, the 
smell. You cannot forget those things.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
