<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990828.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-28 12:45:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Brazilian Archbishop Camara Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazilian Archbishop Dom Helder  
Camara, whose campaigns against social inequality and human rights 
abuses won him international recognition, has died, church leaders 
said Saturday. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	As Archbishop of Recife and Olinda, two neighboring northeastern  
cities in Brazil's poor northeast, Camara earned praise from Pope 
John Paul II, who called him a ``brother of the poor,'' and scorn 
from the military dictators who ruled Brazil, who called him a 
``subversive communist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camara died Friday night at his home in Recife, 1,520 miles  
northeast of Rio, after suffering a cardiac arrest, reports said. 
He had been admitted hospitalized with a urinary infection 10 days 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Camara was a founder of the main Roman Catholic church body in  
Brazil, the National Conference of Brazilian Bishops, and 
continually worked to draw attention to the suffering of the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	He campaigned for the government to combat drought in the dry,  
northeast and spoke out against Brazil's 1964-85 military 
dictatorship. His criticism even led to his home coming under 
gunfire. 
</P>
<P>
	Camara was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize four times,  
although he never received the award. 
</P>
<P>
	Pope John Paul II sent a message to church leaders in Recife on  
Saturday, paying tribute to Camara. 
</P>
<P>
	French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin also issued his condolences.  
``The world has lost with him a great humanist and a free man,'' he 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in the northeastern city of Fortaleza, Camara was ordained  
at age 21. He moved to Rio de Janeiro in his late 20s and set up a 
series of charities before moving back to his native northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sermon of Dom Helder will be always present for us and all  
the church,'' Dom Jose Cardoso Sobrinho, who replaced Camara in 
1995 as Archbishop of Recife and Olinda, said in a radio interview. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
